<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Red Cross workers vote to strike in Connecticut  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Red Cross workers in Connecticut went out on strike
early today after overwhelmingly rejecting the relief agency's
latest contract offer.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 strikers set up a picket line outside the Red Cross
headquarters in Farmington shortly after midnight, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike, the first by Red Cross workers in Connecticut in 25
years, may reduce daily blood collection in the state by 80
percent. But any shortfall will be made up from a national
inventory, said Red Cross spokeswoman Lynn Townshend.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're disappointed, but we remain committed to our mission of
supplying blood and blood products to Connecticut's hospital
patients,'' Townshend said shortly after the strike vote was
announced. ''No patient needs will go unmet.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers, members of AFSCME Local 3145, voted 168-19 to
reject the last contract offer after meeting for several hours in
New Britain. Some of the Red Cross workers called the contract
offer insulting.
</P>
<P>
   The strike involves about 200 employees who conduct blood drives
around the state. It will not affect the work of Red Cross
chapters, such as disaster relief, Townshend said.
</P>
<P>
   Townshend said management will step in and hold only one blood
drive a day, reducing daily collection from 600 units to about 125.
The Red Cross has some 6,500 units in storage, about an 11-day
supply. A unit is slightly less than a pint.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross has said a strike would not immediately affect
Connecticut's blood supply, but a prolonged walkout could
''seriously affect the region's ability to collect and distribute
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The employees include technician-drivers, nurses, phlebotomists
and lab workers. They say they often work long hours, have daily
changing schedules and are being asked to pay a greater share of
their health benefits. Their pay ranges from $10 to $22 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross contends it has made a fair and generous offer,
with pay increases ranging from 3 to more than 5 percent annually.
The proposal is for a three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Jump, the union spokesman, declined to quantify the pay
raises, but said with concessions sought by management factored in
they equal the cost of living or less.
</P>
<P>
   The strike vote came despite the efforts of a federal mediator.
Jump said he hopes the walkout would lead to more negotiations
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would hope the message has been sent loud and clear,'' he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-01-00 0034 </TRAILER>
