<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Livingstone Is Likely London Mayor  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BARR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Barring a sudden massive change of heart by London
voters, their first elected mayor will be a political outcast with
a passion for newts and salamanders, and a genius for annoying
prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Livingstone, known as ''Red Ken'' ever since he led London's
last metropolitan government and gave fits to Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher, is so far ahead in opinion polls before
Thursday's mayoral election that one major betting agency has
stopped accepting wagers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't had a single substantial bet for any of his
so-called opponents for over a month,'' said Graham Sharpe,
spokesman for the William Hill agency.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Britain's political parties fight for the middle
ground, Livingstone is an unabashed survivor from the governing
Labor Party's once-powerful left wing -- a lively relic of the days
when Laborites called each other ''comrade'' and conservative
newspapers railed against the ''loony left.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in the 1980s when Livingstone led the Greater London
Council, churning controversy by supporting gay rights, declaring
the city a nuclear-free zone, cutting subway fares, and making
common cause with Gerry Adams in support of the Irish Republican
Army's violent campaign for a united Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Livingstone says, that's the key to his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   People ''see me as my own man. That's what people want,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published Thursday by the Evening Standard showed
Livingstone with 51 percent support, far ahead of Conservative
Steve Norris at 17 percent and Labor nominee Frank Dobson at 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone survey of 1,004 voters had a margin of error of
about 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone, 54, is a skilled political counter-puncher. He
fought a long, losing battle against Thatcher's determination to
kill the Greater London Council, and he danced away from Prime
Minister Tony Blair's often ham-handed efforts to keep him from
becoming mayor.
</P>
<P>
   However, Blair's government created the mayor's job -- the first
elected mayor in London's history -- as part of its program of
returning some powers to regional and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Though enormously popular with ordinary Londoners, Livingstone
is regarded as a self-aggrandizing flake by many of his Labor
colleagues in the House of Commons, including some who share his
left-wing beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone wanted the Labor nomination, repeatedly swore his
eternal fealty to the party, but concluded he was the victim of a
rigged selection process and ran as an independent. He was then
kicked out of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Skinner, a former ally, says Livingstone as mayor would
''hit the headlines, but you'll never be able to trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I have always viewed him as someone who is an out-and-out
opportunist,'' says David Winnick, a Labor lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The virulence of the attacks contrast with Livingstone's low-key
style. He's a master of the talk show, adroit at turning away wrath
with a quip.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in London, young Kenneth Robert Livingstone was
far more interested in reptiles than in politics, sharing his
bedroom at various times with a South American bullfrog, an
alligator, lizard, salamanders and snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone won a seat on his local government council in 1971
and moved up to the Greater London Council in 1973. At 35, he burst
into national prominence by unexpectedly winning the leadership of
the Labor group, and of the council.
</P>
<P>
   In style and substance, Livingstone's regime in London was
contrary to the Thatcherite norm. He shunned the GLC's official
limousine and rode the subway. He turned down an invitation to the
wedding of Prince Charles and Lady Diana Spencer. ''No one elected
us to go to weddings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More controversially, he met with Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams
and supported the IRA's goal of a united Ireland. In 1983,
Livingstone fanned outrage when he declared that ''what Britain has
done for the Irish nation is, although it is spread over 800 years,
worse than what Hitler did to the Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Livingstone, the GLC offered its financial support of gay
rights, feminists, racial minorities and a group called Babies
Against the Bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it was him being brazen and wanting to be
outrageous,'' says Illtyd Harrington, Livingstone's deputy for a
time at the GLC. ''There is a little bit of Ken that wants to drop
his trousers in public.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the GLC is most fondly remembered for its attempts
to slash subway and bus fares -- a plan thwarted by Thatcher's
government and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Thatcher decided to abolish the council. Livingstone
fought back by posting London's unemployment figures in big numbers
on the County Building, clearly visible to lawmakers across the
Thames in Westminster Palace. He also launched an expensive
advertising campaign stressing London's right to its own
government.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone's marriage ended in divorce in 1973, and he now
lives with Kate Allen, director of Amnesty International UK.
</P>
<P>
   Since the GLC's abolition, he has written a book titled ''If
Voting Changed Anything They'd Abolish It,'' became a restaurant
reviewer for the Evening Standard, and earned more than $240,000 as
an after-dinner speaker, often entertaining the capitalists he
excoriates by day.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Livingstone was forced to apologize to the
House of Commons for failing to fully disclose his outside
earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
