<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Talks Resume  </HEADLINE>
By DANA BUDEIRI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EILAT, Israel (AP) -- Squabbling in Israel's ruling coalition and
Palestinian protests over a plan to expand a Jewish West Bank
settlement have overshadowed the latest round of talks on a final
peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations resumed briefly Sunday in this Red Sea resort amid
accusations by the Palestinians that a plan to build 174 new homes
in the Jewish settlement of Maale Adumim showed that Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak either would not or could not make the
concessions necessary for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is struggling for support from parties in his coalition
who oppose territorial concessions to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Talks scheduled to resume today were expected to focus on the
framework agreement for a final treaty and the final Israeli troop
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross was to arrive in the region
Tuesday to try to push the talks forward. The latest round is aimed
at achieving a framework for a permanent peace between Israel and
the Palestinians, along with agreement on the scale and location of
the third and final troop withdrawal that Israel has promised to
make.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said a disclosure Sunday that
Israel has approved the expansion of Maale Adumim was destroying
Palestinian trust in Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prime minister is concentrating not on the peace talks but
on his coalition talks,'' Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians hope to establish an independent state in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured in 1967, and they
see Jewish settlements there as dangerous obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   The resumption of talks was delayed five hours while the
Palestinians registered a bitter complaint with Israeli negotiator
Oded Eran over the planned expansion.
</P>
<P>
   After less than two hours of talks, Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators took a break from the tense atmosphere for a swim
together in the hotel's outdoor pool.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, meanwhile, lobbied Cabinet ministers Sunday to support
his plan to give three Arab suburbs of Jerusalem to the
Palestinians as a trust-building gesture. Hard-liners warn that the
move would give the Palestinians a foothold in the disputed city,
claimed by both sides as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said the handover was necessary to give the Palestinians
territorial integrity, something they want for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is proper that the (areas) be under Palestinian security
control,'' Barak told reporters. ''This does not weaken
Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which is expected to be proposed at Wednesday's
Cabinet meeting, the villages would move from joint control to full
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Yisrael B'Aliya, an immigrants party, and the National Religious
Party, a patron of Jewish settlers, said they opposed the gesture,
and the NRP said it would bolt the government if Barak went ahead
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday, Barak met with Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, the spiritual
leader of his largest coalition partner, the ultra-Orthodox Shas
party, after weeks of tension between the two leaders. Barak is
trying to win Shas' support for his peace policies by handing over
funds to Shas' religious school system -- a move opposed by the
dovish Meretz party, another coalition partner.
</P>
<P>
   Barak aide and Cabinet Minister Haim Ramon said that without
coalition support, Barak would not be able to hand over the
villages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
