<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First President's Home Saved  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The riverboat slid through the night, and when
her captain sighted the famous house on the steep bank above the
Potomac he followed long-established custom and rang the ship's
bell in salute.
</P>
<P>
   The bell awakened a cabin passenger, Louisa Cunningham, who came
out on deck for a moonlit view of Mount Vernon, home of George
Washington, first president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1853 and the house where Washington had died 54 years
earlier was clearly a wreck. Its roof sagged. Its pillared portico
was painfully propped with raw wooden beams.
</P>
<P>
   The image was still vivid when Mrs. Cunningham wrote her
daughter, Ann Pamela Cunningham, who was in Philadelphia recovering
from an operation:
</P>
<P>
   ''I was painfully distressed at the ruin and desolation of the
home of Washington, and the thought passed through my mind: Why was
it that the women of his country did not try to keep it in repair,
if the men could not do it? It seems such a blot on our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The words struck a spark.
</P>
<P>
   The first historic preservation project in the United States was
soon under way. And as Mrs. Cunningham had envisioned, it was run
by women. Her daughter took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was an opportune moment. Mount Vernon was for sale, but only
to the right buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The estate was owned by John Augustine Washington Jr., the
president's great-grandnephew. He was unable to earn a profit from
its lands and therefore could not maintain the house and grounds.
But he insisted that Washington's home should not be exploited by
private interests. He would sell only to the state of Virginia or
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Pamela Cunningham was then 37 and a semi-invalid. But she
had found an inspiring project.
</P>
<P>
   Surmounting the difficulties then placed in the way of women,
Miss Cunningham formed a corporation, The Mount Vernon Ladies'
Association of the Union. She enlisted allies to lobby the Virginia
legislature in Richmond. In March 1856 it passed legislation
allowing the transfer of the Mount Vernon mansion and 200 acres to
the association under state supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Ritchie, wife of the editor of the Richmond Enquirer, who
had helped in the effort, offered congratulations:
</P>
<P>
   ''Mount Vernon is secure -- is ours! We may be sure of that,''
she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The congratulations were premature. The owner balked.
</P>
<P>
   John Augustine Washington Jr. was suffering from bruised
feelings. He had been criticized for attempting to sell his family
legacy in the first place. Now he felt the latest arrangement was
intended ''to put an indignity upon him.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Cunningham won a point when she visited Mount Vernon in the
summer of 1856 and assured Washington she thought he had been
unfairly abused.
</P>
<P>
   Watching his face, she thought she had touched ''the obstacle no
money could have removed.''
</P>
<P>
   But reaching final agreement on the sale and a purchase price of
$200,000 took two more years.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1858, the owner conceded in a letter that ''the women
of the land will probably be the safest, as they will certainly be
the purest, guardians of a national shrine.''
</P>
<P>
   When the association took possession in 1860 the house was empty
except for a globe, the clay model of a bust of the first president
and the key to the Bastille sent to George Washington by the
Marquis de Lafayette after the French Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   There was a postscript.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the sale the federal Union that Washington helped
found broke apart. The most urgent mission for the new owners of
Mount Vernon was to keep the war from destroying the place.
</P>
<P>
   John Augustine Washington Jr. was killed in combat in September
1861 while fighting for the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   By 1874, when Miss Cunningham stepped down as the association's
regent, Mount Vernon's future was assured.
</P>
<P>
   She had a final wish: Allow George Washington's home to remain
as close to his time as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let one spot in this grand country of ours be spared from
change,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The story of the saving of Mount Vernon is told in ''Mount
Vernon Is Ours,'' by Elswyth Thane, published by J.B. Lippincott
Co. in 1967. The spring issue of the journal ''Colonial
Williamsburg'' features an article by Robert A. Seilig entitled
''Mount Vernon After Washington: The Rescue of an American
Memory.'' Mount Vernon is still owned and managed by The Mount
Vernon Ladies' Association.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on the White
House, Congress and the history of Washington for more than 30
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 0131 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000501.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Renews Criticism of Senate  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- President Clinton is renewing his criticism of
the Republican-led Senate for its slowness in confirming dozens of
his judicial appointments, particularly those of women and
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Sunday to the Detroit chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, Clinton said a
recent study showed that women and minorities took longer to be
considered and were rejected more often than white males.
</P>
<P>
   ''When it comes to appointing judges, the United States Senate
is not doing what it ought to be doing, especially with regard to
women and minority appointees,'' the president told an enthusiastic
audience of about 9,000. ''Vote them up or down. Let us know how
you stand.''
</P>
<P>
   As of early March, when two of Clinton's more controversial
appointees won Senate confirmation, there remained 73 federal
judicial vacancies, or about 10 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited a Michigan appellate judge, Helene White, who has
waited for a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing for three years --
longer than any other pending nominee. A nominee who was in
Sunday's audience, Kathleen McCree Lewis, would become the first
black woman ever to serve on the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
if approved.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a shame, and we ought to be doing something about it,''
the president said of the slow pace.
</P>
<P>
   In response to similar Clinton comments earlier this year, Sen.
Orrin Hatch, the Judiciary Committee chairman, said more than half
the nominees that his panel reported to the full Senate in 1999
were women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''But if the nominee is a judicial activist or is for some other
reason unqualified to serve for a lifetime appointment on the
federal bench, that nominee should not and will not have the
support of the Senate,'' the Utah Republican added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also touched on race relations, saying that if granted
one wish, ''I would wish for our country to be truly one America.''
</P>
<P>
   But his long-promised prescription to improve race relations,
the ''One America Agenda,'' has gone through several drafts and the
White House has no timetable on when, if ever, it will be released.
Clinton offered no glimpses of detail in his Sunday speech, either.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, say that the government's ability to turn
chronic budget deficits into surpluses and move 7 million people
from welfare to work are examples of what can be accomplished when
Americans of all backgrounds work together.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe everybody counts. Everybody should have a chance.
Everybody has a role to play. And we all do better when we help
each other,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In a commencement address earlier Sunday at Eastern Michigan
University in Ypsilanti, Clinton said he would send Congress
legislation intended to better protect the privacy of individual
financial and medical records.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one should have to worry that the results of their latest
physical exam could deny them a home mortgage or a credit card,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In this information age we can't let new opportunities erode
old, fundamental rights We can't let breakthroughs in technology
break down the walls of privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan would, in many cases, require a company to tell
customers it was going to share sensitive consumer information such
as medical and insurance records, or lists of what people buy and
where they buy it.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would give consumers the option not to have
that information shared, and give consumers a new right to review
their credit reports for errors.
</P>
<P>
   The plan stands little chance of passing Congress in this
election year, however. Much of the financial services industry is
opposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 0138 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000501.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Hearings on Elian Not Definite  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional hearings on the government's
seizure of Elian Gonzalez may never happen, despite Republican
demands for an inquiry into the Justice Department's use of force,
a key lawmaker says.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said he
will need to see the government's documents before deciding whether
such proceedings are warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once we get those, I think we can make an intelligent
appraisal as to whether hearings should be held or not. Whether we
should go forth, whether we shouldn't,'' Hatch said Sunday on NBC's
''Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if hearings might not be held at all, he replied: ''If
they're not justified, I guess there won't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said Hatch's reasoning for postponing the proceedings
gives Republicans a graceful way to bow to public opinion, which
polls show has overwhelmingly swung against a congressional
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ''I doubt there will be hearings, and there shouldn't be
hearings,'' Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the top Democrat on
Hatch's committee, said on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of no hearings is a stark departure from the
demands of GOP congressional leaders last week, who accused
Attorney General Janet Reno of prematurely ending negotiations with
the 6-year-old Elian's relatives in Miami and ordering an
excessively forceful raid on their home.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents seized Elian on April 22 and reunited him with
his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez. The pair, along with Elian's
stepmother and infant half brother are staying a secluded retreat
on Maryland's Eastern Shore.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Thursday to Reno, Hatch gave the Justice Department
24 hours to turn over all documents ''related to (1) surveillance
of the Miami home, including but not limited to the possibility of
weapons in that home; (2) seeking and obtaining the search warrant
and the arrest warrant; (3) the decision to enter the home and the
means of entry, and (4) the conduct of the operation of entering
the home, seizing the boy, and taking him to Maryland, including
but not limited to any tactical plan or rules of engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department announced it was unable to comply with
the request in 24 hours, and with the blessing of Republican
leaders, Hatch postponed the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   While those proceedings might never take place, Hatch and others
said questions still need to be answered about the legality of the
agents' search warrant, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ends don't justify the means here,'' Hatch said. If he
schedules any hearings, Hatch said he would ask Reno to testify,
but probably not Elian's Miami family.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats said they would support forward-looking hearings
on how to improve the immigration system.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we ought to take a look in a very dispassionate way at
all of the cases ... and see if there isn't a better way of handing
these matters,'' said Sen. Dianne Feinstein of California. She
added that she believes Reno followed the law.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans kept up their attacks on Reno, saying photos showing
gun-toting agents grabbing a sobbing Elian raises questions about
whether the Constitution still protects Americans against the
government's excessive use of force.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration seems ''to only have two speeds:
either warped speed, aggressive all-out send-in-the-storm-troopers,
or no speed at all, as in the investigation of campaign finance
abuses and Chinese involvement,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., said on ''Fox News Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether there would be hearings, Lott replied: ''We have a
commitment to have the hearings. But it is hard to go forward with
hearings when basic documents you requested have not been
received.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
