<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Renews Criticism of Senate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- President Clinton is renewing his criticism of the
Republican-led Senate for its slowness in confirming dozens of his judicial
appointments, particularly those of women and minorities. In a speech Sunday to
the Detroit chapter of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People, Clinton said a recent study showed that women and minorities took longer
to be considered and were rejected more often than white males. As of early
March, when two of Clinton's more controversial appointees won Senate
confirmation, there remained 73 federal judicial vacancies, or about 10 percent
of the total.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israeli-Palestinian Talks To Resume
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EILAT, Israel (AP) -- Squabbling in Israel's ruling coalition and Palestinian
protests over a plan to expand a Jewish West Bank settlement have overshadowed
the latest round of talks on a final peace treaty. Negotiations resumed briefly
Sunday in this Red Sea resort amid accusations by the Palestinians that a plan
to build 174 new homes in the Jewish settlement of Maale Adumim showed that
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak either would not or could not make the
concessions necessary for peace. Talks scheduled to resume Monday were expected
to focus on the framework agreement for a final treaty and the final Israeli
troop redeployment.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Expected To Endorse Bush
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Arizona Sen. John McCain said Sunday he will endorse Texas
Governor George W. Bush when they meet next week. Overhauling federal campaign
finance laws was the signature issue of McCain's now suspended campaign for the
Republican presidential nomination. Bush opposes some proposed reforms. But
McCain said that discord would not preclude an endorsement of Bush, the
all-but-declared GOP presidential nominee, since the two agree on other areas in
need of change, including Social Security, the military, education and health
care.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S.: AIDS Is Risk To National Security
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- White House officials Sunday defended their decision to
classify AIDS as a threat to national security -- a designation aimed at
garnering more attention and funding toward combating the disease worldwide.
Sandy Thurman, director of the White House Office of National AIDS Policy, said
AIDS has become such an epidemic that, in years to come, it threatens to
destabilize nations and the economies of whole continents. The Clinton
administration has designated about $325 million to fighting the disease
worldwide this year, most of it going to Africa.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sheppard Family To Challenge Verdict
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- The jury verdict rejecting the claim that Dr. Sam Sheppard
was wrongfully imprisoned for killing his wife in 1954 will be challenged, the
Sheppard family's lead attorney said Sunday. On April 12, a jury unanimously
rejected the wrongful imprisonment claim filed in the case that helped inspire
''The Fugitive'' TV series. Gilbert said he would file a motion on Monday asking
Cuyahoga County Common Pleas Court Judge Ron Suster to set aside the verdict or,
as an alternative, grant another trial. Suster presided at the civil trial.
Cuyahoga County Prosecutor William Mason said the Sheppard side had gotten a
fair chance to present its case and predicted the verdict would stand.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NAACP Wants S.C. King Bill Vetoed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The NAACP, fighting to bring the Confederate flag down
from the South Carolina Statehouse, has asked Gov. Jim Hodges to veto a bill
that would create a Martin Luther King Jr. holiday alongside one honoring the
Confederacy. Hodges plans a major ceremony Monday -- planting a tree grown from
a seedling from Selma, Ala. -- to honor the King holiday. South Carolina was the
last state in the nation to create a day for the slain civil rights leader. The
legislature approved the King Holiday bill in April after a bitter fight in the
Republican-controlled House.
</P>
