<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Mayor Hosting Dems' Convention  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE DeARMOND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- He's rich, Republican and, come August,
responsible for helping showcase Democrat Al Gore's pursuit of the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Leading his city in playing host for the Democratic National
Convention, Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan may end up the one
Republican whose praises Democrats sing this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Democratic convention is a huge plus for the city of Los
Angeles, and that's my first love. My first love is not the
Republican Party,'' the slender, reserved mayor said in an
interview a few days before his 70th birthday Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan already has called the Aug. 14-17 convention his top
priority and even participated in a high-profile Beverly Hills
fund-raiser with President Clinton that drew director Steven
Spielberg and other Democratic Party stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ''irony of ironies,'' said H. Eric Schockman, associate
professor of political science at the University of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Riordan's wife is a Democrat, he has golfed
and jogged with Clinton and is comfortable with both parties.
</P>
<P>
   More a businessman than a politician, the New York native sees
the convention through the eyes of a corporate executive: He hopes
to boost not only Los Angeles' economy but also the image of the
nation's second-largest city before an expected 50,000 journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a footnote, it shows that a Republican can put on a better
Democratic convention than a Democrat, or, to put it another way,
than a Democrat can put on a Republican convention,'' said Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Convention will be held July 31-Aug. 3
in Philadelphia, where one Democratic mayor helped secure the bid
and another will be in office during the event.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said that after months of disorganization and poor
communication among Democratic convention planners, he ''sort of
woke up three months ago'' and jumped in. He ousted the host
committee's president and installed his deputy mayor in the job.
</P>
<P>
   He also works the phone for contributions, recently securing
donations from Republican entertainment moguls Rupert Murdoch and
A. Jerrold Perenchio.
</P>
<P>
   Now things are, by all accounts, moving along, and Democrats are
quietly breathing a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for example, said at the Beverly Hills fund-raiser,
''We were a little slow off the block, but I think we're in good
shape now.'' The president acknowledged he was ''a little bit''
surprised to see Riordan there but credited the influence of the
mayor's Democratic wife, Nancy Daly Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Convention Committee is responsible for
events inside the convention, but the city's host committee handles
major outside issues: raising money, overseeing transportation and
working with police to ensure protesters don't shut down parts of
the city as they did at world financial meetings in Seattle and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The convention will be one of Riordan's last big events before
he leaves office next year.
</P>
<P>
   It caps a brief political career that began with appointments by
Democratic Mayor Tom Bradley to the Recreation and Parks Commission
and the Coliseum Commission. A multimillionaire investment banker
and lawyer, Riordan ran for his first elective position in 1993
when Bradley left office.
</P>
<P>
   Spending millions of his own money and portraying himself as an
outsider, Riordan overcame a crowded field of candidates and then
won a close runoff against an Asian-American Democrat. The victory
marked the first time a Republican had been elected to the
nonpartisan office in more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan was re-elected in 1997, beating Democratic state Sen.
Tom Hayden, Jane Fonda's former husband.
</P>
<P>
   He has accepted just $1 a year as mayor, making clear he's not
in politics for the money.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan is comfortable around both major parties and has been
suggested as a possible U.S. secretary of education. He won't rule
it out but says he'd rather work with local school districts,
including perhaps Los Angeles' troubled system.
</P>
<P>
   His choice for president? He sent an endorsement letter to humor
columnist Dave Barry.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's the only one who has committed to do absolutely nothing
if he's elected,'' Riordan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 0206 </TRAILER>
