<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers Hope To Find Woman's Body  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD BENKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- When Girly Chew Hossencofft failed to
show up for work at Bank of America nearly eight months ago, her
co-workers knew they would likely never see her again.
</P>
<P>
   Her boss called police. Within hours, her bloody clothing was
found along a rural highway and her purse was found in the middle
of an Albuquerque street. Damp carpet with bleached-out bloodstains
was found at her home.
</P>
<P>
   Her estranged husband, Diazien Hossencofft, and his 46-year-old
girlfriend, Linda Henning, are charged with murder in a case that
has made headlines in Mrs. Hossencrofft's native Malaysia. Bail for
each was set at $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In November, a grand jury handed down a 27-count indictment
against Hossencofft and a 20-count indictment against Henning, that
includes charges of murder, kidnapping, conspiracy and
evidence-tampering. No trial date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants could face the death penalty if convicted,
prosecutors say, although the defense disputes that. It is rare for
defendants to face execution when the alleged murder victim is
missing.
</P>
<P>
   Both defendants maintain their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent John Schum said bank employees told him that Mrs.
Hossencofft, 36, reported threats by her 34-year-old husband of six
years over the couple's final years and ''that if she ever
disappeared, they should expect the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   ''She was very afraid of him. She feared for her life,'' said
her boss, Kathy Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   Hossencofft, who also vanished when his wife disappeared, was
arrested Sept. 21 in Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   A witness told grand jurors that Hossencofft twice tried to get
him to help kill Mrs. Hossencofft, who had left her husband in
February 1999 and obtained a restraining order against him.
</P>
<P>
   ''When she didn't show up, I knew something was wrong,'' Freeman
said, recalling the day she disappeared, Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks passed, and fellow employees were sure she was dead,
Freeman said. They set up a floral shrine in her memory.
</P>
<P>
   ''She had a teller cage that no one had touched since she
left,'' Freeman said. ''There were flowers all over her cage.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman says Girly Chew apparently met Hossencofft while
vacationing in California. She had worked at two banks in Malaysia
and often visited America as a tourist. She married Hossencofft
about a year before she began working in Albuquerque. The couple
had no children.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, who lives on Penang island in northern Malaysia, was
hesitant to talk much about his only daughter's disappearance,
saying it wouldn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ''My daughter's gone. There's no hope. She's no more,'' he told
The Associated Press from Kuala Lumpur. ''Although she's missing,
the chances are very slim that she's still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 10, a highway worker found her bloody blouse, shorts
and panties along with a bloodstained tarpaulin along U.S. Route
60, just west of Magdalena.
</P>
<P>
   Police have scoured the wind-swept area, 100 miles southwest of
Albuquerque and also have searched the foothills of the Sandia
mountains east of Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Paul Spiers said the continuing
search is about to intensify again in an area he declined to
identify. Prosecutors have asked for blood samples from the family
to compare DNA with blood evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Hossencofft, who was born in Houston and raised in Texas,
Oklahoma, California and Arizona, denies killing his wife or
dumping her body, defense attorney Ron Koch said. Hossencofft has
an idea about what happened to her, Koch said, but added that he
cannot divulge that theory.
</P>
<P>
   Born Armando Chavez Jr. on March 5, 1965, he changed his name to
Diazien Hossencofft in an Albuquerque court in July 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''As I heard it, he had wanted to incorporate within his own
name, according to him, the strains of the master races,'' Germanic
and Asian, Spiers said.
</P>
<P>
   Henning's public defender, Trienah Meyers Gorman, says her
client maintains her innocence. She also says the defense does not
believe the aggravated circumstances required in a death-penalty
prosecution exist in this case.
</P>
<P>
   When Hossencofft was arraigned on Jan. 14, he grinned throughout
the proceedings. Reporters asked about it as he was led away.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no reason not to smile,'' he told them.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press reporter Alvin Ung in Malaysia contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 0211 </TRAILER>
