<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Leaders Step Up Pressure  </HEADLINE>
By SUZAN FRASER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Leaders of Turkey's governing coalition
were looking for support today to ensure their candidate's win in a
second round parliamentary vote for president.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmet Necdet Sezer, a top judge and advocate of reforms,
captured a majority of votes in a first round of balloting last
week, but failed to get the 367 votes needed for an outright
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sezer lost despite receiving the endorsement of the leaders of
all of the parties in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   A second round of voting was expected today.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the governing coalition have launched a behind
the scenes campaign to convince independent-minded lawmakers to
back Sezer, the Hurriyet newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Mesut Yilmaz, the leader of the Motherland Party, planned to
speak with each lawmaker from his party thought to have failed to
back Sezer in last week's vote, Hurriyet reported. Motherland is a
member of the governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said another coalition partner, the Nationalist
Action Party, was also lobbying its members for support.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit has repeatedly spoken out in favor
of Sezer.
</P>
<P>
   Sezer received 281 votes in the first round secret ballot. That
would be sufficient for a victory in a third round of voting, when
only 276 ballots are required.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Mr. Sezer is not elected in the second round, he will
certainly win in the third round,'' said Yilmaz. ''But those
candidates who have no chances to win should pull out before the
second round.''
</P>
<P>
   Sezer closest adversary won only 61 votes.
</P>
<P>
   But with eight other candidates still in the race, many analysts
believe the election will extend to a third round.
</P>
<P>
   That would be another blow to coalition leaders, who have had
increasing trouble enforcing party discipline. In April, deputies
snubbed Ecevit's attempt to amend the constitution and give
President Suleyman Demirel another term.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Sezer -- the 58-year-old chief justice of the
Constitutional Court -- could be a catalyst for democratic reforms
in a country frequently criticized for restricting freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   As head of Turkey's constitutional court, he has called for a
major overhaul of the constitution -- drawn up under the scrutiny of
the leaders of the 1980 military coup -- saying it restricted
freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   Sezer has also openly criticized restrictions on the use of the
Kurdish language, banned in schools and broadcasts. Speaking the
language was only made legal in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey does not recognize its 12 million Kurds as a minority,
and views Kurdish cultural identity as a threat to the Turkish
state.
</P>
<P>
   Sezer's election would likely please the European Union, which
says Turkey's candidacy to the union depends on sweeping reforms to
its freedom-curbing laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 0238 </TRAILER>
