<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, May 1, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Memo Addresses White House E-mail
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- White House officials prepared to tell Congress as early
as February 1999 about a glitch in their e-mail system and to begin retrieving
thousands of unarchived messages that might be relevant to investigators. But
they never followed through, an internal memo shows. The memo, a set of talking
points for testimony before congressional appropriators, laid out the history of
the problem. It disclosed that presidential aides had solicited a bid on Oct.
20, 1998, from contractor Northrup Grumman to retrieve e-mails that weren't
archived because of the glitch.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Time Warner Drops ABC Affiliates
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   UNDATED (AP) -- An impasse over transmission rights between Time Warner Inc.
and The Walt Disney Co. has caused 11 Disney-owned ABC affiliates to be dropped
from the Time Warner Cable system during the May sweeps period. Michael Luftman,
spokesman for Time Warner, said about two million homes on the East Coast lost
their ABC signal shortly after midnight Sunday. A total of 3.5 million homes
nationwide were to be affected. In New York, a scrolling message from the cable
company under the headline "Disney Has Taken ABC Away From You" said the move
came "despite our best efforts to avoid this situation."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Turkish Leaders Step Up Pressure for Candidate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Leaders of Turkey's governing coalition were looking
for support Monday to ensure their candidate's win in a second round
parliamentary vote for president. Ahmet Necdet Sezer, a top judge and advocate
of reforms, captured a majority of votes in a first round of balloting last
week, but failed to get the 367 votes needed for an outright victory. Sezer lost
despite receiving the endorsement of the leaders of all of the parties in
parliament. A second round of voting was expected Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Renews Criticism of Senate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- President Clinton is renewing his criticism of the
Republican-led Senate for its slowness in confirming dozens of his judicial
appointments, particularly those of women and minorities. In a speech Sunday to
the Detroit chapter of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People, Clinton said a recent study showed that women and minorities took longer
to be considered and were rejected more often than white males. As of early
March, when two of Clinton's more controversial appointees won Senate
confirmation, there remained 73 federal judicial vacancies, or about 10 percent
of the total.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israeli-Palestinian Talks To Resume
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   EILAT, Israel (AP) -- Squabbling in Israel's ruling coalition and
Palestinian protests over a plan to expand a Jewish West Bank settlement have
overshadowed the latest round of talks on a final peace treaty. Negotiations
resumed briefly Sunday in this Red Sea resort amid accusations by the
Palestinians that a plan to build 174 new homes in the Jewish settlement of
Maale Adumim showed that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak either would not or
could not make the concessions necessary for peace. Talks scheduled to resume
Monday were expected to focus on the framework agreement for a final treaty and
the final Israeli troop redeployment.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Expected To Endorse Bush
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Arizona Sen. John McCain said Sunday he will endorse
Texas Governor George W. Bush when they meet next week. Overhauling federal
campaign finance laws was the signature issue of McCain's now suspended campaign
for the Republican presidential nomination. Bush opposes some proposed reforms.
But McCain said that discord would not preclude an endorsement of Bush, the
all-but-declared GOP presidential nominee, since the two agree on other areas in
need of change, including Social Security, the military, education and health
care.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S.: AIDS Is Risk To National Security
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- White House officials Sunday defended their decision to
classify AIDS as a threat to national security -- a designation aimed at
garnering more attention and funding toward combating the disease worldwide.
Sandy Thurman, director of the White House Office of National AIDS Policy, said
AIDS has become such an epidemic that, in years to come, it threatens to
destabilize nations and the economies of whole continents. The Clinton
administration has designated about $325 million to fighting the disease
worldwide this year, most of it going to Africa.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei gained 429.38 points to close at 18,403.08. 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees 7, Blue Jays 1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Paul O'Neill hit a three-run double and Roger Clemens got
his 249th career win in the New York Yankees' 7-1 victory over the Toronto Blue
Jays on Sunday. Clemens allowed one run, seven hits and two walks in seven
innings. He struck out eight and moved into 38th place on the career victory
list.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
