<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ING Buying ReliaStar for $5.1B  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- ReliaStar Financial Corp., the eighth largest
publicly-held life insurance company in the United States, is being
sold to Dutch financial giant ING Group NV for about $5.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ING will also assume $1 billion in ReliaStar debt under terms of
the deal announced today.
</P>
<P>
   ING has been looking for a U.S. life insurer for two years. It
already owns Equitable of Iowa and the U.S. investment firm Furman
Selz. With the addition of ReliaStar, it will have completed a
major part of its international strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ReliaStar, which had revenues of $3.04 billion in 1999, had been
mentioned as a potential takeover target by several possible
suitors, including General Motors Corp. and Wells Fargo &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The company's subsidiaries offer life insurance and annuities,
employee benefits products and services, retirement plans, life and
health reinsurance, mutual funds, and bank and trust products. It
has $38.4 billion in assets under management.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction values ReliaStar at $54 a share. The U.S.
company's stock rallied 43 percent Friday to $43 a share on the New
York Stock Exchange on rumors that talks were being held with ING.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is expected to close late in the third quarter
of this year, subject to regulatory and ReliaStar shareholder
approval. The companies expect to be fully integrated by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ReliaStar will continue its operations as part of ING Americas
and retain current management. ReliaStar's chairman and CEO John
Turner will become a member of the executive committee ING Americas
and become vice chairman of the Americas region.
</P>
<P>
   Based on revenue from insurance premiums, the Amsterdam-based
ING currently ranks 19th in the U.S. life insurance market.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, ING acquired Equitable of Iowa for $2.2 billion. One
month later it purchased the investment bank Furman Selz for $600
million.
</P>
<P>
   ING expects to cut annual costs by up to $65 million by 2005 if
the ReliaStar deal goes through as planned.
</P>
<P>
   According to ING, combined revenues from insurance premiums in
1999 would have been $12.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Minneapolis, ReliaStar employs 3,800, while ING has
about 90,000 staffers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 0835 </TRAILER>
