<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 9:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Monday, May 1, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time Warner Drops 11 ABC Stations
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A quarrel over transmission rights between Time
Warner Inc. and The Walt Disney Co. left 11 Disney-owned ABC
stations off of local cable systems. The only way for cable
customers to see ABC programs would be to rig their TVs to get ABC
the old-fashioned way, through an antenna. A total of 3.5 million
homes nationwide were affected in seven key markets, according to
Michael Luftman, spokesman for Time Warner. Cable customers were
without ABC programming in New York City; Los Angeles; Houston;
Raleigh-Durham, N.C.; Toledo, Ohio; and small parts of Time Warner
systems in Fresno, Calif., and Philadelphia. The move comes in the
midst of May sweeps, the period when ratings are used to set local
advertising rates.
</P>
<P>
   Construction Spending Report Due
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department reports on
construction spending for March today. Construction spending rose
1.5 percent in February with commercial projects and single-family
homes posting big gains. In January, construction spending rose 2.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Purchasing Managers Report Due
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The National Association of Purchasing
Management issues its report on the industrial economy during April
at 10 a.m. EDT today. The purchasing managers index was at 55.8
percent in March, down from 56.9 February. A reading of 50 or over
indicates growth.
</P>
<P>
   Actors Set For Rallies Over Contract
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The first major Hollywood strike since
writers walked out in 1988 was set to begin today with union actors
planning rallies in Los Angeles, New York City, San Francisco and
Chicago. The actors said they refuse to perform in radio and
television commercials until they get a larger chunk of the booming
cable TV business. In Los Angeles, actors planned to march to the
Wilshire Boulevard offices of several ad agencies, Screen Actors
Guild spokesman Greg Krizman said. SAG and the American Federation
of Television &AMP; Radio Artists, representing about 135,000 actors,
authorized the walkout last month.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper Competition Trial To Begin
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The future of newspaper competition in San
Francisco will be shaped in federal court this week as the Hearst
Corp. defends its purchase of the San Francisco Chronicle and the
subsidized transfer of the San Francisco Examiner to a local
publisher. A lawsuit by Clint Reilly, a former mayoral candidate
and unsuccessful bidder for the Examiner, contends the Chronicle
purchase was rigged and that the Examiner's transfer is a sham,
designed to give Hearst a local newspaper monopoly after more than
a century of competition. The trial begins today and is scheduled
to last all week.
</P>
<P>
   6 of Top 10 CEOs Head Computer Firms
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Six of the nation's 10 highest paid chief
executives work for high-tech firms, according to Forbes magazine.
The magazine, in a report released yesterday, ranked executives
running the nation's top 800 companies by their total compensation
packages for 1999, including salary, bonuses and stock gains. No. 1
on the list was Charles B. Wang, head of Computer Associates
International Inc. of Islandia, N.Y., with a 1999 compensation
package totaling $650.1 million, Forbes said. He had ranked 39th in
1998. Two other newcomers to the top 10 -- who weren't even listed
last year -- were Bobby R. Johnson Jr., chief executive of Foundry
Networks Inc. in San Jose, Calif., and Stephen M. Case, head of
America Online Inc. in Dulles, Va. Johnson's compensation totaled
$230.5 million, giving him the No. 2 ranking, while Case collected
$117.1 million to land in the No. 6 spot.
</P>
