<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Insurer Ends Debt Repayment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Daiichi Mutual Fire and Marine Insurance
Co. gave up Monday on efforts to repay its debts, becoming Japan's
first nonlife insurer to fail since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The Finance Supervisory Agency, Japan's financial industry
watchdog, forbade Daiichi from taking on new customers, although
the insurer will continue making payments to current clients, FSA
chief Masaharu Hino said.
</P>
<P>
   The FSA and the Marine and Fire Insurance Association of Japan
have assigned administrators to look for a purchaser of the failed
insurer's assets.
</P>
<P>
   They will also investigate alleged falsification of financial
reports at the company. Earlier this month, Japan's Financial
Supervisory Agency found that Daiichi had concealed that it was
insolvent at the end of March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The administrators will decide whether to file a criminal suit
against Daiichi executives, said Noboru Araki, executive director
of the Marine and Fire Insurance Association.
</P>
<P>
   Daiichi's failure comes amid rapid change in Japan's financial
sector, which the government is trying to liberalize and make more
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Koichi Hirai, president of the Tokyo-based firm, said he and
other top managerial officials are ready to take ''any criticism''
for the company's failure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really don't know what excuse to make,'' Hirai said at a
televised news conference.
</P>
<P>
   After the FSA found the inconsistencies in Daiichi's financial
reports the regulator told Daiichi to boost its capital.
</P>
<P>
   Under that order, Daiichi sought fresh capital injections from
Japanese and foreign companies, but failed to attract funds quickly
enough, Daiichi said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the company's decision to give up restructuring, the
FSA ordered Daiichi to suspend part of its operations, including
the issuance of new contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Daiichi was set up in 1949 and became Japan's eighth-largest
nonlife insurer with assets totaling $13.08 billion, according to
the Nihon Keizai business daily.
</P>
<P>
   A recent decline in returns on investment and an increase in bad
loans left it with debts that exceeded assets by $451 million at
the end of March, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
