<HEADLINE> S.Korea Reports April Trade Surplus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's trade surplus shrank to
$220 million in April, down sharply from $2.4 billion a year ago,
the Trade Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It pushed the country's cumulative trade surplus during the
first four months of the year to $773 million, down from $7 billion
in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   In April, exports rose by 18.6 percent to $13.64 billion, while
imports surged by 47.4 percent to $13.42 billion, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
   The government blamed the lackluster performance on labor
strikes by autoworkers and a disease outbreak in early April that
blocked exports of pork and other meat.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's car workers staged a one-week joint strike in
early April, opposing the planned sale of ailing Daewoo Motor Co.
to a foreign investor.
</P>
<P>
   Also contributing to the reduced trade surplus were rising
demand for raw materials and capital goods and high oil prices, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   With crude oil prices stabilizing, South Korea expects that its
trade balance will improve considerably in May.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea spent $2 billion on oil imports in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 1004 </TRAILER>
