<BODY>
<HEADLINE> dow Up 15; Nasdaq Up 65  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A modest advance by technology stocks led the
broad market higher at the start of trading today. Microsoft rose
in the first session since the Justice Department asked a federal
court to split the company in two to satisfy antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 15.20 at 10,749.11.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 65.40 at 3,926.06, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 7.46 at 1,459.89.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose 2 31/64 to 72 15/64. Late Friday afternoon, the
Justice Department and 17 states delivered their propsed remedy for
Microsoft's antitrust violations: splitting the company into one
business for Microsoft's Windows operating-system software, and one
for Microsoft's Office and other applications products, plus
Microsoft's Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was widely expected, and many investors decided
that the possibility of a breakup had already taken its toll on
Microsoft stock. Before today's session, Microsoft's share price
had declined by about 40 percent since the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies that compete with Microsoft were mostly
higher. Red Hat, which sells the Linux operating system, was up 3
3/8 to 28 7/16. VA Linux rose 5 3/8 to 47.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems, a leading maker of computer servers and
workstations, rose 11/16 to 92 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 111.62 million
shares, behind Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.32 to 510.57.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.4 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was up 2.7 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 2.4 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   	   ------
</P>
