<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manufacturing Grows at Slower Pace  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN ALT POWELL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- America's industrial sector grew for the 15th
consecutive month in April, though at a slower pace than in March,
while prices for raw materials didn't rise as fast as in earlier
months, the National Association of Purchasing Management reported
today.
</P>
<P>
   The purchasing managers' group said that its manufacturing
index, based on a national survey of executives who buy raw
materials and other supplies for industries, registered 54.9
percent in April, slightly weaker than the 55.8 percent reported
for March and the lowest since a 54.4 percent reading last August.
April's number was below the 55.5 percent that Wall Street analysts
had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Any reading above 50 indicates growth, however.
</P>
<P>
   The purchasing managers' index is watched closely because it is
the first national reading for April on the U.S. industrial
performance, a key sector of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The overall picture is one of continuing growth in
manufacturing activity during the month of April,'' Norbert J. Ore,
chairman of the association's survey committee, said in a statement
accompanying the report.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that the index ''trend for the last six
months indicates deceleration in the rate of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ore noted that price increases for raw materials continued, but
at a slower rate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It also appears that the recent decline in energy prices has
not found its way through the manufacturing sector this month,''
Ore added. ''This should give hope to further declines in the
prices index in the near term.''
</P>
<P>
   The index of prices paid by manufacturers was 76 percent in
April, down from 79.8 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Camilli, director of economic research for the Tucker
Anthony investment firm in New York, said the report showed ''a
strong level of economic activity with some hints of building
inflationary pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported last week that the U.S. economy
grew at a sturdy annual rate of 5.4 percent in the first quarter,
down from a roaring 7.3 percent annual rate the in fourth quarter
of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Camilli, who expects to see a 4 percent annual growth rate in
the April-June quarter, said the latest reports indicate that ''the
economy is growing at an overly robust pace.''
</P>
<P>
   This could spur Federal Reserve policy makers to raise interest
rates further to slow growth and head off inflation. The Fed has
raised rates a quarter of a point six times since last June.
Camilli expects an increase of a half a percentage point when the
Fed meets May 16.
</P>
<P>
   The purchasing managers' report said that 16 of 20 industries
reported improved business in April.
</P>
<P>
   The survey indicated that 17 industries were paying higher
prices. The price index has been above 50 percent for 12
consecutive months.
</P>
<P>
   The report also indicated that manufacturing inventories are
still being liquidated, with the inventory index registering 45.2
percent in April, down from 48.4 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   The index of new orders showed continuing growth at 56.3 percent
in April, but it was down slightly from 56.9 percent the month
before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
