<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gen. Clark Bids Farewell to Kosovo  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Outgoing NATO commander Gen. Wesley
Clark visited Kosovo today for the last time during his term,
bidding farewell to the leaders he's worked with in an effort to
end violence in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 55, finishes his term as supreme commander of NATO forces
in Europe on Wednesday. He arrived today in Kosovo's provincial
capital, Pristina, to meet with U.N. mission chief Bernard Kouchner
as well as ethnic Albanian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   After his formal meetings, Clark is to take a walk down the
provincial capital's main street, where he received a hero's
welcome last year after NATO's 78-day bombing campaign forced
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to withdraw his forces from
Kosovo. That withdrawal opened the way for an international
presence here.
</P>
<P>
   Still, full peace has not been achieved. Since the NATO-led
peacekeepers and the U.N. mission arrived in June 1999, an
estimated 100,000 Serbs have fled the province as a result of
revenge attacks by ethnic Albanians. The ethnic Albanians were
seeking to get even for a bloody crackdown that was ordered by
Milosevic and ended by the NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   In the ethnically divided city of Kosovska Mitrovica, Clark
crossed for the first time into the northern, Serb-controlled side
of the city. There he met with a leading hard-line Serb, Oliver
Ivanovic.
</P>
<P>
   After Clark returned to local NATO command headquarters in the
southern, Kosovo Albanian section, Ivanovic told reporters he was
satisfied with the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope the high American official realized that we Serbs are
no wild nation,'' Ivanovic said. He said the two discussed the
return of hundreds of thousands of Serbs who fled Kosovo before
NATO deployed there last June.
</P>
<P>
   Clark is being succeeded as NATO commander by Air Force Gen.
Joseph Ralston, 56. As is traditional, Ralston also will be
commander of U.S. European Command, in charge of all 100,000 U.S.
forces in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Also today, Secretary of Defense William Cohen was to meet
American troops serving in the Kosovo peacekeeping force. He and
Clark were not scheduled to meet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
