<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dry Forecast Lifts Grain, Soybeans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices climbed in early
dealings today on the Chicago Board of Trade, propelled by
forecasts for mostly dry weather this week in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Corn and soybeans both hit one-month highs in the first
half-hour of trading, with corn briefly touching the 12-cent daily
limit.
</P>
<P>
   New forecasts called not only for drier weather than previously
forecast for next weekend, but for hot and dry conditions in
growing regions over the next 30 to 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   As farmers make swift progress with their spring plantings,
concerns are increasing that a dry-weather pattern is re-emerging
after a spate of April showers. Dry forecasts are reviving fears
that drought could limit this year's crop yields.
</P>
<P>
   The forecasts affected corn and soybeans the most -- primary
products from the nation's midsection -- but wheat also was pulled
higher by the rally in grains.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery rose 6} cents to $2.61{ a bushel; July
corn rose 10\ cents to $2.42\ a bushel; July oats rose 4\ cents to
$1.26 a bushel; July soybeans rose 21} cents to $5.61 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures retreated in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .02 cent to 69.25 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle fell .05 cent to 84.77 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell .38 cent to 76.27 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell .30
cent to 99.25 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
