<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pill Makers Settle With Government  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The producers of the dietary supplement
''Vitamin O'' agreed Monday to repay consumers $375,000 in a
settlement of government charges that the product didn't do what
they claimed it would, federal regulators said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would end the government's lawsuit against Donald
L. Smyth, president and sole shareholder of Rose Creek Health
Products, Inc. and The Staff of Life, Inc., both of Kettle Falls,
Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ''Vitamin O'' promised customers a $25 bottle
of pills could treat or prevent hosts of chronic or
life-threatening ailments, from heart disease to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The pills were essentially overpriced placebos, according to the
Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement bars Smyth and his companies from claiming
''Vitamin O'' is effective in treating life-threatening diseases,
or that its effectiveness has been established by medical or
scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth and his companies also would be prohibited from making any
claims about the health benefits or safety of any other food, drug
or dietary supplement.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Smyth nor the companies admitted any wrongdoing in
reaching the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. District Court judge must sign the deal before it is
finalized.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the net: http://www.ftc/gov
</P>
</TEXT>
