<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up118; Dow Up 99  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks rose for a third straight
session today, leading the broad market higher. Microsoft rose in
the first session since the Justice Department asked a federal
court to split the company in two to satisfy antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 99.90 at 10,833.81, building on early gains.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 118.97 at 3,979.63, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 20.34 at 1,472.77.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose 3 11/16 to 73 7/16. Late Friday afternoon, the
Justice Department and 17 states delivered their propsed remedy for
Microsoft's antitrust violations: splitting the company into one
business for Microsoft's Windows operating-system software, and one
for Microsoft's Office and other applications products, plus
Microsoft's Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was widely expected, and many investors decided
that the possibility of a breakup had already taken its toll on
Microsoft stock. Before today's session, Microsoft's share price
had declined by about 40 percent since the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether split up, or not, the sum of the parts are worth
around $125 to 135 a share,'' said Michael E. Stanek, a Microsoft
analyst with Lehman Brothers. ''Therefore, investor objections of
not owning the stock based on 'break-up' fears are no longer rooted
in reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies that compete with Microsoft were mostly
higher. Red Hat, which sells the Linux operating system, was up 3
13/16 to 28 7/8. VA Linux rose 6 11/16 to 48 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems, a leading maker of computer servers and
workstations, rose 3/4 to 92 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's advance was led by General Electric, which rose 3 7/16
to 160 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Today, some modest support for the stock market came from the
National Association of Purchasing Management, which said America's
industrial sector grew for the 15th consecutive month in April. The
group said the economy's growth came at a slower pace than in
March, while prices for raw materials didn't rise as fast as in
earlier months.
</P>
<P>
   That offered some relief to inflation-wary traders. Most market
watchers expect the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates for the
sixth time in a year when it holds its next meeting on May 16. The
indication of modest growth raised hopes that only a modest,
quarter-point increase is in the cards.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 401.52 million
shares, behind Friday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 11.53 to
517.78.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
