<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fox's 'Party of Five' Says Goodbye  </HEADLINE>
By CHELSEA J. CARTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- From the beginning, the fictional, orphaned
Salinger siblings overcame obstacles, struggling to stay together
after their parents' death -- and also to stay on the air after the
network nearly pulled the plug on their first television outing.
</P>
<P>
   Season after season, audiences tuned in to find out what hurdle
was next for the tight-knit fictional brood of ''Party of Five'' as
they coped without parental guidance.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the family faces one final obstacle -- making their
own way in the world in the two-hour series finale, airing at 8
p.m. Eastern on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we attempted to wrap everything up,'' said the
show's co-creator and co-executive producer Christopher Keyser.
''What we tried to do was deal head-on with the central issue of
the show: How long does a family need to stay together?''
</P>
<P>
   The series told the story of five siblings whose parents were
killed by a drunken driver. Older brother Charlie (Matthew Fox)
took on the unwanted job of family patriarch to his brothers and
sisters: Bailey (Scott Wolf), Julia (Neve Campbell), Claudia (Lacey
Chabert) and Owen (Jacob Smith).
</P>
<P>
   ''We always felt the idea of the show was not an idea that was
worth exploring forever,'' said Amy Lippman, the other co-creator
and executive producer. ''It was about a family that was dealing
with the death of their parents. That can only go so far. We always
knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   Its demise, though, was hastened this year when the show was
moved to a new time slot, its ratings sagged and the cast's
contracts expired. Several cast members, including Campbell and
Wolf, who have burgeoning film and stage careers, were unlikely to
return.
</P>
<P>
   Keyser and Lippman also left the daily operation of the show
this season to pursue the ''Time of Your Life'' spinoff, which has
been temporarily pulled from Fox's schedule. They returned to
oversee the final ''Party'' episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last three months has very much been about preparing to
say goodbye,'' Keyser said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the show that almost wasn't. In its first year, Fox
nearly canceled the show until a fervent campaign by viewers and
media critics surfaced. TV Guide featured ''Party of Five'' as the
first of its annual ''The Best Show You're Not Watching'' picks.
</P>
<P>
   During the show's six-year run, the siblings faced a myriad of
problems, including confronting the driver who killed their
parents, an episode that earned Keyser and Lippman the Humanitas
Prize for writing. The show also picked up a Golden Globe for best
drama series in its second season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Party of Five'' never shied away from tough stories:
</P>
<P>
   --Julia struggled with the question of abortion after becoming
pregnant by her high school boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   --Bailey battled alcoholism and was confronted by his family in
an emotional intervention. Later, he nearly killed his girlfriend
in a car accident, lost his license and attended Alcoholics
Anonymous meetings.
</P>
<P>
   --Charlie survived Hodgkin's disease.
</P>
<P>
   --Claudia dealt with the aftermath of attempted date rape.
</P>
<P>
   --Owen acted out violently when he no longer was the center of
attention for the siblings.
</P>
<P>
   The clan also faced drug problems, deaths, domestic violence and
many, many broken hearts.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the show's tiny moments -- buying a dress for prom,
getting married without Mom and Dad looking on, and the weekly
dinner out together that lent the series its title -- that were its
finest.
</P>
<P>
   It's that element that shines brightest in the finale with a
series of flashbacks -- not of the big story lines, but of intimate
moments. These remind viewers why they hung in all those years.
</P>
<P>
   The siblings face leaving their protective family circle in San
Francisco to pursue their own lives. Bailey debates going to
college in Pennsylvania. Julia contemplates taking an internship in
Washington, D.C. Claudia is offered a scholarship to a music
school. Charlie mulls selling the house.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, their decision is simple, emotional and, most of
all, real.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody leaves home.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   'DATELINE NBC': Haunted by the memory of taking someone's life,
Richard Luttrell carried around a picture of the first soldier he
killed in Vietnam. But it was the image of the little girl who also
appeared in the photo that burned brightly in Richard's mind.
Thirty-three years later, he resolved to find the girl, and set out
on a journey that would lead him back to Vietnam to face his own
past. On Monday's edition of ''Dateline NBC,'' correspondent Keith
Morrison reports a story of memory and mystery. It airs at 8 p.m.
Eastern.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
