<DOCNO> APW20000501.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Seeks Remains of Soldiers  </HEADLINE>
By KYONG-HWA SEOK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAEHWASAN, South Korea (AP) -- Lee Kyong-soo, a retired army
staff sergeant, watched Monday as soldiers hacked at a mountainside
with picks and shovels, searching for remains of troops slain in
the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   ''We fought here until we ran out of bullets. My fellow soldiers
died here, one after another. It still hurts to think of them,''
said the tearful 71-year-old Lee, who wore a military uniform
bedecked with medals.
</P>
<P>
   He was at a battlefield where about 1,100 South Korean soldiers
fought invading North Korean troops only two days after the Korean
War broke out on June 25, 1950. Most of the South Koreans were
killed in a three-day battle, and their remains were never
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Half a century later, South Korean soldiers began digging up the
Kaehwasan Mountain on the outskirts of Seoul in a search for the
remains. None was found Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The excavation is part of a government plan to commemorate the
50th anniversary of the 1950-53 Korean War. Soldiers are digging in
two other areas and plan to increase the number of excavation sites
to 26 by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Before the digging began, government officials, veterans and
children of slain soldiers burned incense and prayed before a stone
memorial tower in a traditional show of respect for the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Park Soon-hwan, a Buddhist monk, was 2 when his father, Sgt. 1st
Class Park Sang-rae, died at Kaehwasan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a shame that the remains of my father and other soldiers
have been buried here, abandoned for 50 years,'' Park said. ''I
feel grateful that they started this, even belatedly.''
</P>
<P>
   The government says it is doing the work now because it has the
money, technology and manpower to do so. An impoverished South
Korea was preoccupied with economic recovery in the years after the
war.
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul, U.S. and South Korean officials began field research
Monday to excavate an area at Seoul National University Hospital
this week. At least two sets of remains of American soldiers who
died in the Korean War are believed to be buried at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The planned recovery work at the hospital was prompted by
reports that workers found human bones and rusted helmets that were
possibly American during drainage work there in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, the remains of 42 people believed to be U.S.
soldiers have been recovered in North Korea in joint recovery
operations. Most have not been identified.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 sets of remains believed to be those of South Korean
soldiers have been uncovered in other sites since April. The Seoul
government estimates the soldiers missing from the Korean War at
100,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the Korean War, South Korea and a U.S.-led U.N. force fought
communist North Korea, which was backed by the Soviet Union and
China.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 million Korean civilians and hundreds of thousands of
South and North Korean soldiers died. About 54,000 Americans died,
and 8,100 were listed as missing.
</P>
<P>
   The United States still keeps 37,000 troops in South Korea. No
peace treaty was signed at the end of the Korean War, and the
Korean peninsula remains tense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 1308 </TRAILER>
