<HEADLINE> Monday's Supreme Court Actions  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The Supreme Court took these actions Monday:
<TEXT>
<P>
   --Agreed to decide in an Illinois case whether police who suspect
people of having illegal drugs in their homes can keep them from
going inside alone until a search warrant can be obtained.
</P>
<P>
   --Ruled in a Texas case that state and local governments can tell
their employees when to take the compensatory time off that they
agree to receive instead of overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   --Refused to disturb the State Department's designation of an
Iranian dissident group, the People's Mojahedin Organization of
Iran, as a terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   --Threw out some of a Texas man's convictions for sexually
assaulting his stepdaughter. The 5-4 decision said those
convictions were wrongly based on a state law enacted after he
allegedly committed the crimes, reinvigorating language the court
used in a similar ruling 202 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   --Let stand a ruling in a New York case that says Internet
service providers are not legally and financially liable when
someone is defamed in e-mail communications or bulletin board
messages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
