<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To End Satellite System Dimming  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton ordered a halt today to the
military's long practice of intentionally dimming the pinpoint
accuracy of global positioning devices now used to help steer cars,
fly planes and find missing skiers and hikers.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, civilians using a U.S.-built network of satellites
for navigation got a less accurate reading than the military out of
fear that potential enemies could use the system to target
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight, the United States will stop jamming the signal for
civilian users, but will still selectively block the improved
service to regions of the world where the U.S. percieves a threat,
a White House statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision follows development of new technology that makes
that kind of regional blocking possible, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in accuracy will mean a civilian will be able to
know the position of a car, ambulance or skier within about the
dimension of a tennis court. Now, the accuracy is more like within
the dimension of a football field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
