<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Monday, May 1, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC Gone From 7 Time Warner Systems
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A quarrel over transmission rights between Time
Warner Inc. and the Walt Disney Co. left seven Disney-owned ABC
stations off of local cable systems today. The only way for cable
customers to see such ABC programs as ''Good Morning America''
would be to rig their TVs to get an ABC station the old-fashioned
way, through an antenna. A Time Warner spokesman said a total of
3.5 million homes in seven markets were affected. Cable customers
were without ABC programming in New York City; Los Angeles;
Houston; Raleigh-Durham, N.C.; Toledo, Ohio; and small parts of
Time Warner systems in Fresno, Calif., and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Shares Up on Breakup Plan
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of Microsoft were up 3[ at 72~ this
afternoon as Wall Street painted the government's bid to split the
software maker into two companies as both unrealistic and maybe
even beneficial for investors in the stock. Many legal and industry
experts suggest that the plan is too severe and also unworkable,
and may not survive when Microsoft challenges it in the court of
appeals. In addition, the appeals process and ultimate resolution
of the case may take two years or so. Meantime, it's suggested,
investors may eye the two proposed companies favorably. The split
was recommended by the federal government and 17 states as
punishment for violating antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Up 102; Dow Gains 163
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors decided today that the possibility of
a breakup of Microsoft had already taken its toll, and rising
shares of the software giant lead the entire technology sector
higher. Companies that compete with Microsoft, including Red Hat
and VA Linux, also were higher. Just before 3 p.m., the Dow
industrials were up 163.42 at 10,897.33. On the NYSE, advancers led
decliners 1,837-1,045. The Nasdaq was up 102.28 at 3962.94.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   New York (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EDT:
