</P>
<P>
   Construction Spending Rose in March
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Spending on construction projects around the
country rose by 1.4 percent in March, led by a burst of activity in
big government projects. It was the third straight monthly
increase. The Commerce Department reported today that construction
spending was a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $765.2 billion, a
better showing than analysts had anticipated. Many were forecasting
no change and some others thought there would be a small decline.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing Grows at Slower Pace
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. industrial sector grew for the 15th
consecutive month in April, while price increases for raw materials
did not rise as fast as in earlier months, the National Association
of Purchasing Management reported today. The purchasing managers'
group said that its manufacturing index, based on a national survey
of executives who buy raw materials and other supplies for
industries, registered 54.9 percent in April, slightly weaker than
the 55.8 percent reported for March. April's number was below the
55.5 percent that Wall Street analysts had expected. However, any
reading above 50 indicates growth.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Firms To Curb Profit Claims
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators said today that 14 online
trading firms or individuals have agreed to stop claims that the
trading strategies and systems they sell can make investors easy
money with little risk. The firms neither admitted to nor denied
wrongdoing. The Federal Trade Commission, the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission and the Securities and Exchange Commission
announced settlements with the firms in which they agreed to drop
unsubstantiated claims of profits. The federal agencies also warned
consumers to be wary of false and misleading claims on Web sites
touting trading strategies or systems.
</P>
<P>
   Power Cos. May Team on Transmission
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Six power companies in the Northwest are in talks
to create a joint venture combining all of their power transmission
assets, a move that would make their network the second largest in
the region. Puget Sound Energy spokeswoman Dorothy Brackens said
today that her company was in ''preliminary discussions'' with five
other companies: Avista Corp. of Spokane, Montana Power Co. in
Butte, Mont., Portland (Ore.) General Electric Co, and two
Nevada-based companies owned by Sierra Pacific Resources of Reno,
Nev. The Wall Street Journal, which first reported on the venture
today, said the new company would manage power lines and
substations in Washington, Oregon, Idaho, Montana, Wyoming and
Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi Shrugs Off Euro Weakness
</P>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- European Commission president Romano Prodi shrugged
off weakness of the euro as temporary and insisted that the
fundamentals of Europe's economy were sound. Prodi, meeting with
reporters after talks with Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori,
said he raised the subject of the European currency, which has been
weak in relation to the Japanese yen and U.S. dollar. ''In my
opinion the euro began well. The European Central Bank organized
itself in the way it should have organized itself. The fundamentals
of the European economy are sound,'' said Prodi, citing inflation
and development.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens To Buy Medical Tech Co.
</P>
<P>
   MALVERN, Pa. (AP) -- Siemens Medical Engineering Group is buying
Shared Medical Systems Corp., one of the world's leading suppliers
of services and information technology systems for the healthcare
industry, for $2.1 billion. The companies said today that they
expect the cash tender offer of $73 a share to be launched within
10 days. Shared Medical was the target of a $2 billion hostile bid
in March from Eclipsys Corp. of Delray Beach, Fla. Shared Medical
dismissed the $67 a share offer.
</P>
<P>
   Companies Can Dictate Time Off
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Public employees who agree to take extra time
off instead of collecting overtime pay can be forced to use the
time off at their employer's convenience, the Supreme Court ruled
today. The justices, voting 6-3 in a case from Houston, said
governmental employers have the authority to control when such
time-off credits are used if no pre-existing labor agreement says
otherwise. The decision is a setback for 127 sheriff's deputies in
Harris County, Texas, and the AFL-CIO, which had supported their
legal argument.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever Repeats Ben &AMP; Jerry Pledge
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Ben Cohen and Jerry Greenfield, wearing jeans
and rumpled sport shirts, today traveled to decidedly dressed-up
Park Avenue, where they got another round of assurances from their
new multinational bosses that selling their Vermont-based ice cream
company wouldn't mean selling out their ideals of social activism.
The two hippie capitalists heard Unilever's U.S. chief executive,
Richard A. Goldstein, repeat his earlier promises that Ben &AMP;
Jerry's Homemade will operate as an independent entity. The
co-founders said they'll press Unilever to take a greater role in
social causes, but questioned how successful they'd be.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch Numico To Buy Rexall Sundown
</P>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- The Dutch specialty foods company
Royal Numico NV is buying Rexall Sundown Inc., a U.S.-based maker
of nutritional supplements and consumer health products, for about
$1.7 billion. News of the deal disclosed today drove Rexall
Sundown's shares up 4 3/16 or about 21 percent to 23 7/16 in
afternoon New York trading. Rexall, based in Boca Raton, Fla. will
give Numico a strong position in the fast-growing American food
supplements market, the Dutch group said. Numico plans to finance
the deal -- already approved by Rexall's management -- by issuing new
shares and bonds and by refinancing existing loans, according to a
company statement.
</P>
<P>
   China Attracts Taiwan Computer Cos.
</P>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwanese investment in computer and other
hi-tech projects in rival China surged fourfold to $320 million in
the first quarter, the government said today. Officials said more
Taiwanese computer firms were setting up factories in China,
attracted by its vast market and ample supply of engineers and
other technicians. The first quarter electronics investment
accounted for 57 percent of overall Taiwanese investment in China,
said Taiwan's Investment Commission, which approves investment in
China.
</P>
