<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Vietnam Must Fix Economy  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP) -- In an unusually blunt
assessment of Vietnam's ills, a top official said the communist
government must confront some hard realities -- a sagging economy,
rampant corruption and rising drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Ho Chi Minh City Mayor Vo Viet Thanh's comments came after an
invitation-only 25th anniversary celebration of Vietnam's victory
over the United States. Thanh told the aging architects of the 1975
military triumph and 20,000 guests Sunday that the country had
failed the memory of those who died and should feel ''guilty at
heart'' for not doing more to clean up the economy and government.
</P>
<P>
   ''Arbitrary and imperious behavior, wasteful spending,
embezzlement, bribery and other social evils, particularly the
increasingly widespread scourge of drug addiction, are sending
worrying signals of ineffective law enforcement and serious
degradation of moral and spiritual values,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the victory on the battlefield a quarter-century ago
brought the country together, Vietnam's rulers have failed to bring
real prosperity to its 76 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Despite huge potential, including a highly motivated work force,
Vietnam remains among the world's poorest nations, with an average
per capita income of $370 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment, which topped $8 billion in 1996, plummeted
to less than $2 billion in 1999 following the Asian financial
crisis and concerns that Vietnam was unwilling to undertake serious
economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   Thanh said a top priority must be to make the investment
environment more attractive, adding that his city, once known as
Saigon, ''welcomes with open arms'' foreign investors, businessmen,
and multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday's parade on the grounds of the old Independence Palace
-- where communist tanks smashed through the gates on April 30, 1975
-- the focus was the military triumph, although the United States
was never mentioned by name.
</P>
<P>
   Old soldiers, their chests dripping with medals, drew the
loudest applause, along with rifle-toting women from the
''long-haired army'' who were part of the guerrilla campaign
against the Americans. Soldiers on several floats waved bouquets of
fake flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Banners flanking a giant portrait of revolutionary leader Ho Chi
Minh hailed the anniversary of the reunification of communist North
Vietnam and the capitalist South and called on the people to build
an ''economically strong country.''
</P>
<P>
   Only invited guests and participants took part in the palace
festivities, but the celebrations continued throughout the day and
night with an open carnival that drew tens of thousands into the
city streets. In the country's largest-ever amnesty, 12,000
prisoners were released. A mass wedding of 25 couples was also held
at a downtown park.
</P>
<P>
   Average Vietnamese have so far shown patience with the
government, as living standards have slowly crept up in the wake of
the economic reforms launched in 1986. But with the current
slowdown, that patience may start to wear thin.
</P>
<P>
   Dang Duc Hao, 40, an invited parade-watcher who was a teen-age
communist supporter in 1975, said he was very happy to be
celebrating what he called ''one of the most vivid examples of
national liberation in the world,'' but he complained about trying
to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ''My family is in difficulty,'' he said, explaining that his
salary as an electricity worker is very low, his wife is sick and
he doesn't have enough money to support his four children.
</P>
<P>
   Among the thin crowd of spectators outside the palace -- now
called Reunification Palace -- was Nguyen Thi Chinh, 39, who
recalled his problems finding a good job after 1975 because his
sister had married an American. Three years ago, he finally got
work as a driver with a foreign company.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things have gotten better, but I still worry about my
children's future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pham Chi, 70, a retired port worker who came to Ho Chi Minh City
hoping to watch the parade, also wound up standing outside the
palace because he didn't have a ticket. He said the country was
''much more advanced'' than it was a quarter-century ago, when he
watched the palace being bombed just before the city fell to the
communists.
</P>
<P>
   What are his hopes for the next 25 years?
</P>
<P>
   ''I will not be alive in 25 years,'' he laughed. ''Maybe at that
time, the Vietnamese people can fly to the moon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
