<HEADLINE> Reform Party Looks Out For Buchanan  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- National Reform Party leaders are trying to
quell a rebellion among state affiliates hostile to Pat Buchanan by
threatening to block them from voting at the national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who is touring state conventions in pursuit of enough
support to win the nomination, has run into state parties from New
Hampshire to Wisconsin to California willing to change their rules
to keep him out.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just telling people that if they play games, their
delegations will not be recognized at the national convention,''
party chairman Pat Choate said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they're not recognized, they can't be seated and if they
can't be seated, they can't vote,'' added convention chairman
Gerald Moan.
</P>
<P>
   Some state officials see Buchanan's tour across the country as
an attempt to take over the party founded by Ross Perot. Not all
national party leaders are happy with him either.
</P>
<P>
   He is outspokenly anti-abortion, for example, while the Reform
Party platform is silent because the party believes government
should stay out of such private matters. Buchanan's statements
about homosexuals and Nazis sit uneasily with many Reform Party
members. And the Buchanan camp rubbed national leaders the wrong
way last month by proposing to move the nominating convention from
Long Beach, Calif., to Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The Buchanan camp had long proposed a meeting with the national
leaders to smooth things over. On Sunday in Washington, Buchanan's
sister and campaign manager, Bay, repeated the candidate's promise
not to try to force an anti-abortion plank into the party platform.
</P>
<P>
   She promised to think about party secretary Jim Mangia's
proposal that the candidate make a statement acknowledging
differences in opinions on social issues, Mangia said.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the national committee cracked down on state parties,
starting with Illinois, where the state convention was headed for
turmoil on Sunday. State chairman Larry Redmond, according to Moan,
was given the ultimatum by a regional representative and fireworks
were avoided. Buchanan captured most of the state's delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Several state parties have split in two rather than accept
Buchanan or his supporters. Some states, such as Wisconsin, tried
to change the rules to exclude anyone running for party office who
hasn't been a member for more than six months. That would have
blocked many of Buchanan's supporters, since they came to the party
after their candidate bolted the GOP in October. There are now two
Wisconsin Reform Parties.
</P>
<P>
   As many as seven split state parties could end up at the
convention vying for seats and voting rights, Moan said. A
credentialing committee and the full convention will resolve such
disputes, and they won't look kindly on any parties that tried
''exclusionary tactics,'' Moan said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.reformparty.org
</P>
<P>
   http://buchananreform.com
</P>
</TEXT>
