<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Chair Backs Vet Health Care  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation to vastly expand prescription drug
benefits for military retires over age 65 won the crucial
endorsement on Monday of Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman
John Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, R-Va., announced sponsorship of a bill that would extend
to all 1.3 million Medicare-eligible military retirees the same
benefits that are now available to 450,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   That includes an $8 copayment if the prescriptions are filled by
mail order and a 20 percent co-payment when acquired in retail
pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   Warner called the measure ''another step forward in the effort
to keep commitments made to military retirees,'' primarily the
promise of health care for life.
</P>
<P>
   He announced the program in a Senate speech on the eve of action
in his committee on the Pentagon's fiscal year 2001 budget request.
</P>
<P>
   He said in an interview that he is incorporating the benefit
increase in the overall Pentagon measure before the panel.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've held a series of town meetings. We've been in
consultation with a wide range of veterans groups. We've heard from
hundreds and hundreds of individuals,'' Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure backed by Warner has been pushed previously by Sens.
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and Olympia Snowe, R-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pharmacy benefit is the number one issue and priority of
military retirees, since pharmacy needs are the biggest drain on
the pensions of military retirees,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the mail-order and retail pharmacy benefits are only
available to retired military personnel who had been receiving
their prescription drug benefits at medical installations on bases
that have been closed.
</P>
<P>
   Since this covers only about a third of those who are retired,
it led to a dual system.
</P>
<P>
   ''By accident of where you had retired and by the results of the
Base Closure Commission, some retirees received the benefits and
others did not,'' said Kennedy. ''this legislation would treat
military retirees across the country the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 20-year retirees are entitled to free care at
military facilities on space-available basis, or they can join an
HMO-like military health care system known as Tricare. However, at
65, all retirees are switched to Medicare. Under the Medicare
system, there are no prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans complain that the closing of bases has reduced access
to military hospitals by 40 percent, that many health-care
providers are reluctant to deal with Tricare because of poor
efficiency and low reimbursement rates.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton wants to provide all 39 million Medicare
recipients with up to $1,000 a year in prescription drugs
initially, at a cost to each of $26 a month in premiums.
Republicans have balked; they say two-thirds of Medicare
beneficiaries already have private prescription coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
has proposed separate legislation that would expand the Pentagon's
mail-order pharmacy program to Medicare-eligible military retirees
-- but they first would pay a $150 annual deductible.
</P>
<P>
   Warner's measure does not include such a deductible.
</P>
<P>
   His plan would cost an estimated $300 million in the first year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)armed--services/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)warner/releases.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
