<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Connecticut ranks last in reporting rate  </HEADLINE>
sdhfcdtfonrhfon
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Connecticut hospitals rank last in the
nation in the number of incidents per thousand doctors that the
state reports to a national database of problem physicians, The
Hartford Courant reported.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the newspaper said its analysis found that 60
percent of U.S. hospitals have never reported a doctor to the
National Practitioner Data Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The database, which is closed to the public, lists disciplinary
actions, practice restrictions and malpractice payments totaling
$25 billion affecting one out of six doctors in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Eisner, a lawyer representing several hospitals in the
state, said the low reporting rate is due to the high quality of
doctors in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ''Connecticut hospitals are almost all nonprofit; we're up here
in the Northeast, where the education pool is so strong. I honestly
don't think we get the same kind of problems other places get,'' he
told The Courant.
</P>
<P>
   But the newspaper highlighted two cases it said raised questions
about the reporting of problem doctors to the database.
</P>
<P>
   The Courant, using a version of the database with much
identifying information removed, matched those records with court
documents, regulatory files and other sources to identify the
doctors in question.
</P>
<P>
   In one, Dr. Syed Jamal left a three-year cardiac residency
program at Hartford Hospital after one year when senior doctors
questioned his skills.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo which came to light after Jamal sued for wrongful
termination, cardiology chief Dr. David Waters said colleagues
found Jamal ''not effective in emergency situations and looking
after common cardiovascular problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not feel that Dr. Jamal has the skills necessary to
become a good cardiologist and that it would be in his best
interest to find some other type of medicine to practice,'' Waters
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But because there was no disciplinary action against Jamal, the
hospital made no report to the national database. Moreover,
reporting of actions against doctors in training is voluntary, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal ''disagreed violently'' with the conclusion, Waters said.
His wrongful termination case was settled out of court and he has
apparently left the country, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, the newspaper said obstetrician Dr. Brian
Hennessey left Bristol Hospital in 1993 after a difficult
childbirth case which is now the subject of a malpractice lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Courant said it could find no record that Hennessey's
decision to voluntarily relinquish his privileges at the hospital
was reported to the database.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessey, who did not respond to requests for comment from the
newspaper before the story was published, said in a telephone
interview Monday with The Associated Press that his decision to
leave the hospital stemmed from plans to return to his native
Canada and had nothing to do with the delivery.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had put money on a home in Nova Scotia and was
planning to practice medicine there when he left Bristol Hospital.
The move later fell through.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Pat Caputo, a spokeswoman for the hospital, said she could
not discuss details of the case but said the facility strongly
disputes any suggestion that it has ever failed to meet the
reporting requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessey said his 33-year medical record is unblemished except
for the malpractice case involving the birth of Nicholas Caswell.
He said Caswell's mother, Judy Caswell, continued as a patient for
two years after the birth and only filed suit after Hennessey's
ex-wife called her and claimed he had been drinking before the
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor said his ex-wife was bitter because her alimony
payments had been cut.
</P>
<P>
   State medical regulators reviewed the allegations but found them
unsubstantiated. Hennessey called the review process rigorous.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not easy to impress them that you're innocent,'' he said.
''And I proved to them that I was not at fault.''
</P>
<P>
   The malpractice case is still pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-01-00 1650 </TRAILER>
