<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To Create War Reparation Fund  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration and the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce announced Monday the creation of a fund to
solicit donations from American corporations to compensate victims
of Nazi forced labor during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the chamber nor the administration could say how much
American companies might contribute, although Deputy Treasury
Secretary Stuart Eizenstat said ''we certainly hope they will be as
generous as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Johnstone, the chamber's senior vice president for
international affairs, said the project is the result of requests
from a number of member companies who were ''interested in doing
this if the funds go to the victims and not into the pockets'' of
trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber, which represents more than 3 million businesses
worldwide, was approached by the administration and some major U.S.
corporations that have been threatened with lawsuits by survivors
and their heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Several large American corporations, including Ford and General
Motors, have acknowledged that their German subsidiaries benefited
from slave labor after operations were taken over by the German
government during the war.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to compensation for victims of Nazi oppression,
Johnstone said the fund will allow companies to pool resources to
respond to many humanitarian challenges around the world, including
disaster relief following hurricanes and earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   In December, U.S. and German negotiators, at the behest of
President Clinton and German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder,
announced a deal to establish a $5.2 billion German fund to
compensate hundreds of thousands of people forced to work for the
Nazis and German companies during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Under that agreement, German companies would pay roughly half
the restitution and the German government would make up most of the
rest. American firms that had German subsidiaries during the war
have said they would contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat said estimates put the number of slaves and forced
laborers who worked in German factories and farms at 12 million,
with 1 million still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The compensation worked out by the German government and
companies would amount to payments of $7,500 for slave laborers and
$2,500 for forced laborers.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are dignified payments but hardly matching the suffering
they endured,'' Eizenstat said. He called the offer by American
companies to supplement these resources a ''generous gesture'' that
would ''show compassion to a highly visible group of elderly
people.''
</P>
<P>
   New York attorney Melvyn Weiss, who represents some victims,
said that good-faith contributions to the fund might help avert a
class-action lawsuit against at least 50 and perhaps as many as 200
U.S. companies, including Kodak and Exxon-Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the humanitarian aid fund on Monday came at
a chamber-sponsored forum, ''Charting the Way Forward in an Era of
Globalization.''
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat told the business representatives that more needed to
be done to respond to anti-globilization protesters who showed up
in force last fall in Seattle and last month in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many people, especially young people and workers, have the
view that impersonal forces and unfamiliar international
institutions are endangering their jobs and the environment,''
Eizenstat said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. Chamber of Commerce site:
http://www.uschamber.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 1657 </TRAILER>
