<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BUCKLED UP: No special enforcement on first day of new seat beltlaw  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The ticket books have been updated, but New
Jersey State Police didn't plan checkpoints or any other special
enforcement Monday, the first day of a new seat belt law.
</P>
<P>
   Now officers across the state can pull over motorists for not
wearing a seat belt and write them a $42 ticket. The new law
replaces one that allowed cops to issue summonses only if they had
pulled the car over for another reason.
</P>
<P>
   ''The law is on the books, and how it is enforced is up to each
department's discretion,'' said Jeff Lamm, a spokesman for the
state's Division of Highway Traffic Safety.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 15 years, the legal mandate for drivers and
front-seat passengers to buckle up could only be enforced by police
as a ''secondary'' offense.'' The tab for violating that law was
$20 and it carried no additional points or surcharges from the
Division of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But the new law offered by a Burlington County lawmaker makes
not wearing a seat belt a ''primary'' offense.
</P>
<P>
   And the new price tag for offenders is $42, said John Hagerty, a
spokesman for the state police.
</P>
<P>
   All of the troopers patrolling the state's roadways Monday were
aware of the new law, Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their summons books have been updated to reflect the change.
They know it's another law on the books that they can enforce,''
Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   State police were not tallying how many cars were stopped and
their drivers cited under the new law, Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking at it as yet another motor vehicle statute.
Enforcement will be out there,'' Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   But the troopers ''are not going to target any particular
place'' or plan any specific enforcement, Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamm said the highway safety division also had no plans to
collect data on the new law's first day.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Herb Conaway, D-Burlington, sponsored the bill,
saying the change also will benefit children, who are the most
vulnerable to injury in automobile accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Changing the law will also reduce fatal highway accidents and
severe injuries, said Conaway, who is also a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The Seat Belt Safety Coalition of New Jersey has said the
state's 62 percent compliance rate for seat belt use in the state
falls below the national average of 68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The AAA New Jersey Automobile Club reports that 60 percent of
children killed in automobile accidents weren't wearing seat belts.
The safety coalition predicts the greater enforcement will save up
to 50 lives and prevent nearly 2,900 serious injuries per year.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey chapter of the National Motorists Association
opposed the change, arguing that it would be difficult to enforce
and that the number of traffic deaths on New Jersey roads reached a
20-year low in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
