<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Cancer Treatment May Pose Danger  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A compound that seemed like a promising new
weapon in the battle against cancer may face a clouded future
following the discovery that -- at least in the lab -- it kills human
liver cells.
</P>
<P>
   The agent, called TRAIL, has been under investigation for use
against many types of cancer because it causes cancerous cells to
die. It had proven safe in mice and non-human primates and human
tests were on the near horizon.
</P>
<P>
   But a team of researchers led by Stephen C. Strom of the
University of Pittsburgh discovered that human liver cells exposed
to the compound in lab tests were killed. Their findings are being
public in the May issue of the journal Nature Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The drug firms Immunex and Genentech have been working together
on the development of TRAIL. Officials there said they were forging
ahead with the development while also working with Strom, who has
advised them of his findings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are certainly not dismissing Dr. Strom's findings. In fact,
quite to the contrary, we are working closely with him,'' said Doug
Williams, chief technology officer at Immunex.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said there are questions about whether the molecule
used in Strom's tests is exactly the same as the type developed by
Immunex and Genentech and also whether its effect in a working
liver would be the same as in liver cells in a lab test.
</P>
<P>
   He said the companies ''are carrying out the requisite
preclinical and toxicology studies'' and have not yet filed an
application for human trials with the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stan Lipkowitz of the medicine branch of the National Cancer
Institute said Strom's finding is ''a very important piece of
work'' because previous studies have not shown any toxic effects
from TRAIL.
</P>
<P>
   But Lipkowitz, who is not connected with either Strom or the
drug firms, also suggested that the version of the drug used in the
Pittsburgh tests may differ from that under development by the drug
companies and thus may act differently.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Glenn D. Rosen of Stanford University was surprised by
Strom's finding. He suggested that processed cells like those used
in the lab may be sensitized and thus be more likely to react to
TRAIL than cells combined in a liver.
</P>
<P>
   Strom, a professor of pathology, said he made the finding while
studying whether chemicals like TRAIL, that can cause cells to
commit suicide, have any involvement in diseases such as hepatitis
and cirrhosis.
</P>
<P>
   He tested human liver cells infected with hepatitis to see if
they were sensitive to the drug. When the cells were exposed to
TRAIL, they died.
</P>
<P>
   So Strom and his team did a control experiment using healthy
human liver cells. ''To our surprise, it killed the cells. We
repeated it many times and it killed the cells every time,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've shown that differences in the sensitivity of various
species to the same compound can prove critical. Significant
toxicity could result if TRAIL were used in human cancer therapy,''
Strom said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We became worried so we got (the report) out as soon as we
could,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   TRAIL stands for TNF-related apoptosis-inducing ligand, a
chemical that interrupts the normal life cycle of a cell causing it
to commit a form of suicide known as apoptosis.
</P>
<P>
   TRAIL had been considered a promising alternative to TNF -- tumor
necrosis factor -- a close molecular cousin prized for its ability
to boost anti-cancer immunity but impractical to use in the clinic
because it causes septic shock and liver failure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
