<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pulitzer Deals on Post-Dispatch  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Pulitzer Inc. is buying out most of a longtime
partner's interest in its flagship newspaper, the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch, in a deal announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Herald Co. had shared in 50 percent of the newspaper's
profits and capital expenses in an agreement dating to 1961. The
Herald Co., a subsidiary of Newhouse family-controlled Advance
Publications Inc., agreed to reduce that share to 5 percent in
exchange for $306 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also calls for Pulitzer to complete the buyout no
later than 2015.
</P>
<P>
   ''This transaction has special meaning to me, because the St.
Louis Post-Dispatch was the first newspaper owned by my
grandfather, Joseph Pulitzer,'' Pulitzer chairman Michael E.
Pulitzer said. ''I am pleased that we are making this additional
investment in the St. Louis community.''
</P>
<P>
   The original arrangement was tied to a joint operating agreement
involving the Post-Dispatch and the St. Louis Globe-Democrat.
Pulitzer managed the business operations of both papers until 1984,
when the Newhouse family sold the Globe-Democrat. The
Globe-Democrat ceased publication two years later.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new joint venture arrangement is important because it
aligns our responsibility for operations more closely with the
results we achieve,'' said Robert C. Woodworth, president and chief
executive of Pulitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Advance president Donald E. Newhouse said the company's passive
investment in the Post-Dispatch was unique among its newspaper
properties. Advance publishes daily newspapers in 22 cities along
with magazines and other publications.
</P>
<P>
   ''When our partners at Pulitzer indicated their desire to create
a joint venture which would more appropriately reflect their
continuing operating responsibility for the paper, we agreed that
these unique circumstances fully justified the new arrangement,''
Newhouse said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to dilute Pulitzer's earnings 6 percent to
8 percent for the first 12 months, and to become earnings neutral
in the fourth year, Pulitzer officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Post-Dispatch, St. Louis-based Pulitzer
operates the Arizona Daily Star in Tucson, Ariz., and 12 community
dailies, along with Web sites and other new media initiatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
