<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scottish Officials Ready for Trail  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- More than 11 years after the
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103, victims' families were heading toward
a former U.S. Air Force base Monday to witness the trial of two
Libyan suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish court authorities said they were trying to keep the
trial as routine as possible, despite high emotions, hundreds of
reporters and unprecedented security.
</P>
<P>
   The old base, converted into an $18 million high-security
courtroom and detention center, was ringed by police and prison
staff for the start of hearings on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah are charged
with murder, conspiracy to murder and endangering the safety of an
aircraft in the bombing over Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21, 1988.
More than 270 people, 189 of them Americans, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of victims' relatives were expected to arrive in
Amsterdam early Tuesday and make the 40-mile drive to Camp Zeist,
where they will be housed in a nearby hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives will be given priority seating in the courtroom's
public gallery, behind bullet proof glass.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Swire, a spokesman for British relatives, arrived in the
Netherlands last week, eager to see the trial finally begin. ''It's
been a ghastly 11{ years. We expect the fairest obtainable verdict
as to whether these two individuals are guilty or innocent,'' he
told Associated Press Television News.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the court will hold sessions almost daily through
July 28 before adjourning until Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   John Grant, of Glasgow University School of Law, said the
prosecution apparently intends to work backward, first establishing
murder was committed before trying to prove the culpability of the
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a murder trial, after all,'' he said. ''First they have
to prove that there has been a murder.''
</P>
<P>
   The early witnesses will include British aviation experts, as
well as police and investigators who sifted through the debris of
the exploded jetliner after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was expected to cost about $3 million a month, mostly
paid by Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers have alleged that other terrorist organizations
operating in Europe at the time were responsible for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The two defendants were visited Monday by Libya's ambassador in
their detention block -- an area surrounded by high concrete walls
and bales of barbed wire, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They said the defendants were being treated like any suspect
held in pretrial custody in a Scottish jail. They receive visits
from relatives and friends and meet each other and with staff
members each day.
</P>
<P>
   Arrangements were made to provide food that meets Islamic
dietary guidelines. They were given prayer mats, and an arrow was
painted on the floor pointing to the holy city of Mecca for them to
direct their prayers. They also have satellite television links
that receive several Arabic-language channels, the officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
