<HEADLINE> Tehran Police Headquarters Attacked  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Mortar shells exploded near Iran's national
police headquarters in central Tehran on Monday night, wounding six
people, witnesses and state-run Tehran radio said.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's state television said three mortars exploded near a
sports complex in Tehran's Vanak Square.
</P>
<P>
   But sources in the area said several mortars had landed at the
headquarters of the national police forces. Other mortar shells hit
a nearby Armenian club and in the street.
</P>
<P>
   Security forces surrounded the area around the police
headquarters soon after the attack, the sources said, speaking on
condition they not be named.
</P>
<P>
   Tehran radio said six people were wounded, one critically.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel Mujahedeen Khalq group claimed responsibility for the
attack in a call to The Associated Press in Cairo. Spokesman Farid
Soleimani said the police, known as the State Security Forces, were
the intended target.
</P>
<P>
   ''Several military units of the Mujahedeen pounded with mortars
the command headquarters of the State Security Forces,'' Soleimani
said in a call from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Soleimani said the attack was carried out ''in solidarity with
student protests nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Students have been demonstrating against the closure of 16
reformist publications by the Press Court, which is dominated by
hard-liners opposed to President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   State television did not say who was responsible for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi-based Mujahedeen has claimed responsibility for a
number of mortar attacks in recent months in which several people
have been killed or injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
