<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minorities complain about use of scanner on state property  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Black and Hispanic legislators were angry
Monday that a bone-density scanner being used to screen women for
osteoporosis in the state Capitol complex was not useful for
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Assembly members staged an impromptu protest by
posting signs stating ''White women only'' around Bellevue Woman's
Hospital's booth at a health fair.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Matthews, a state worker from Albany who is black, was
among those upset by the test.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't understand why you would bring a machine for white
women only to a public place where there are multiple races. That's
very insulting,'' she said. ''It's like we're back in the '40s and
'50s.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Fidler, who was conducting the tests, said the genetic data
in the machine only applied to white women and she could not verify
the accuracy if the test was performed on nonwhite women. Fidler
agreed to pack up her machine and leave after state Assemblyman
Keith Wright, chairman of the state Black, Puerto Rican and
Hispanic Legislative Caucus, told her it shouldn't be used on
public property.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of white women who had been waiting in line for the
test dispersed. One got into a brief shouting match with
Assemblyman Ruben Diaz Jr. of the Bronx, claiming that he was being
selfish for wanting to deny the test to white women. He told her
she was the selfish one. However, the woman quickly reconciled, and
even hugged, other protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Ten million Americans have osteoporosis, a disease characterized
by deterioration of the bone that can lead to fragility and an
increased risk of fractures, according to the National Osteoporosis
Foundation. The disease is blamed for 700,000 vertebral fractures
annually.
</P>
<P>
   An X-ray machine that can scan nonwhite woman was too large and
expensive to bring to the fair, said Carole Salluzzo, spokeswoman
for Bellevue, located in Niskayuna about 10 miles west of Albany.
She said that heel testing machines like the one at the fair are
not marketed with databases that apply to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''All we were trying to do by having the density (testing
machine) there was just screen the most at-risk population which
are white women unfortunately,'' she said. ''The largest percentage
that have low bone mass are sadly white women. Women of color have
stronger bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the last few years, medical literature has been virtually
devoid of information about bone density in minority women, a
researcher at University of Connecticut's Center on Aging has said.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, conventional wisdom was that black women did
not get osteoporosis because they seemed to achieve a genetically
higher peak bone mass. The disease is much more prevalent in white
and Hispanic women.
</P>
<P>
   But a University of Connecticut study that performed bone
density scans on 100 black volunteers older than 65 found that
one-third of the women had osteoporosis or experienced enough bone
loss to put them at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-01-00 1718 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
