</P>
<P>
   ABC Off From 7 Time Warner Systems
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In an escalating corporate dispute, ABC was
blacked out in the homes of 3.5 million Time Warner cable customers
around the country today -- just as the ratings ''sweeps'' period
was beginning and Regis Philbin was about to quiz celebrities on
''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' The only way many viewers could
see ABC shows was by disconnecting the cable and rigging up an
antenna. The Walt Disney Co., ABC's corporate parent, is fighting
over how much money Time Warner must pay Disney for the right to
carry some of its cable channels. The affected customers were in
seven markets served by ABC-owned television stations. About 1.5
million were in the New York City area, 665,000 in Houston and
440,000 in Raleigh-Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing, Construction Rise
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's manufacturing sector grew in April,
though at a slightly slower pace than the month before. The
increase in prices for raw materials also moderated. Yet the
figures from the National Association of Purchasing Management --
along with a separate government report of a surprising rise in
construction spending in March -- indicate such a strong economy
that Federal Reserve policy-makers may feel compelled to raise
interest rates more aggressively when they meet later this month,
economists said. Several analysts predicted a one-half percentage
point hike in short-term rates at the meeting May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators Target Web Traders
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fourteen online trading firms or individuals
have agreed to stop making claims that the trading strategies and
systems they sell can bring investors easy money with little risk,
federal regulators said today. The firms neither admitted nor
denied wrongdoing. The Federal Trade Commission, the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission and the Securities and Exchange
Commission announced settlements with the firms in which they
agreed to drop unsubstantiated claims of profits. The federal
agencies also warned consumers to be wary of false and misleading
claims on Web sites touting trading strategies or systems.
</P>
<P>
   Power Cos. May Team on Transmission
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Six power companies in the Northwest are in talks
to create a joint venture combining all of their power transmission
assets, a move that would make their network the second largest in
the region. Puget Sound Energy spokeswoman Dorothy Brackens said
today that her company was in ''preliminary discussions'' with five
other companies: Avista Corp. of Spokane, Montana Power Co. in
Butte, Mont., Portland (Ore.) General Electric Co, and two
Nevada-based companies owned by Sierra Pacific Resources of Reno,
Nev. The Wall Street Journal, which first reported on the venture
today, said the new company would manage power lines and
substations in Washington, Oregon, Idaho, Montana, Wyoming and
Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi Shrugs Off Euro Weakness
</P>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- European Commission president Romano Prodi shrugged
off weakness of the euro as temporary and insisted that the
fundamentals of Europe's economy were sound. Prodi, meeting with
reporters after talks with Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori,
said he raised the subject of the European currency, which has been
weak in relation to the Japanese yen and U.S. dollar. ''In my
opinion the euro began well. The European Central Bank organized
itself in the way it should have organized itself. The fundamentals
of the European economy are sound,'' said Prodi.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens To Buy Medical Tech Co.
</P>
<P>
   MALVERN, Pa. (AP) -- Siemens Medical Engineering Group is buying
Shared Medical Systems Corp., one of the world's leading suppliers
of services and information technology systems for the healthcare
industry, for $2.1 billion. The companies said today that they
expect the cash tender offer of $73 a share to be launched within
10 days. Shared Medical was the target of a $2 billion hostile bid
in March from Eclipsys Corp. of Delray Beach, Fla. Shared Medical
dismissed the $67 a share offer.
</P>
<P>
   Companies Can Dictate Time Off
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Public employees who agree to take extra time
off instead of collecting overtime pay can be forced to use the
time off at their employer's convenience, the Supreme Court ruled
today. The justices, voting 6-3 in a case from Houston, said
governmental employers have the authority to control when such
time-off credits are used if no pre-existing labor agreement says
otherwise. The decision is a setback for 127 sheriff's deputies in
Harris County, Texas, and the AFL-CIO, which had supported their
legal argument.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever Repeats Ben &AMP; Jerry Pledge
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Ben Cohen and Jerry Greenfield, wearing jeans
and rumpled sport shirts, today traveled to decidedly dressed-up
Park Avenue, where they got another round of assurances from their
new multinational bosses that selling their Vermont-based ice cream
company wouldn't mean selling out their ideals of social activism.
The two hippie capitalists heard Unilever's U.S. chief executive,
Richard A. Goldstein, repeat his earlier promises that Ben &AMP;
Jerry's Homemade will operate as an independent entity. The
co-founders said they'll press Unilever to take a greater role in
social causes, but questioned how successful they'd be.
</P>
