<HEADLINE> Search Reopens For U. of Fla. Head  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- The search for a new University of
Florida president is starting over again because the last two
candidates pulled out Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Adam Herbert told a search committee for the state's
flagship university in Gainesville that Auburn University President
William Muse had withdrawn. Muse said he felt his time and talents
could be better used at Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, James Catanese, president of Florida Atlantic
University, said he had been asked by students, staff members,
community leaders and university benefactors to stay on at the
school in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   Six candidates were recommended to the search committee by a
consulting firm, but Herbert said some of them were discouraged by
a faculty group resolution that called all the candidates
unqualified.
</P>
<P>
   He also said some wanted to avoid having their backgrounds made
public record, as required by Florida's Sunshine Law.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Florida's former president, John Lombardi,
stepped down Nov. 1 after 10 years in the $250,000-a-year post. His
interim replacement, Charles Young, a retired UCLA chancellor, has
agreed to stay until a permanent replacement is found.
</P>
</TEXT>
