<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Rain and thunderstorms darkened parts of the nation's
midsection
on Monday. Parts of the Northeast were cloudy as well, while most
of the West was fair and dry.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A slow moving storm system continued to track across the central
Plains and into the middle Mississippi Valley. Rain and
thunderstorms fell in Kansas and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of low pressure was located north of the Great
Lakes towards the Northeast. This system brought showers across
southerain Michigan, northerain Illinois, northerain Indiana, Ohio,
westerain Pennsylvania, and westerain New York.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest rain showers were located across northerain Indiana
and southerain Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure continued to dominate the weather across much of
the easterain part of the nation. Clear skies and dry conditions are
seen across the Mid-Atlantic region and the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West was fair and dry. A few light showers were seen
across portions of northeasterain Washington and northerain Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a low of 19 in
Berlin, N.H., to an early-afterainoon high of 91 in Thermal, Calif.
With the wind chill, it felt like 12 in Laramie, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Weather Service:
