<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Co. Buys Life US Insurance Co.  </HEADLINE>
By KARREN MILLS, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- ReliaStar Financial Corp., the nation's
eighth-largest publicly held life insurance company, is being
acquired by ING Group of the Netherlands in a deal valued at $6.1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase announced Monday follows ING's 1997 purchases of
Equitable of Iowa for $2.2 billion and the investment bank Furman
Selz for $600 million. With the addition of ReliaStar, the Dutch
financial group will have completed a major part of its
international strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ''ReliaStar can be a perfect fit with our existing businesses,''
said Ewald Kist, who takes over as ING chairman Tuesday when
Godfried van der Lugt retires.
</P>
<P>
   ReliaStar's operations include life insurance and annuities,
employee benefits products and services, retirement plans, and
mutual funds. It has $38.4 billion in assets under management.
</P>
<P>
   Based on revenue from insurance premiums, Amsterdam-based ING
currently ranks 19th in the U.S. life insurance market. The merged
company will be among the top 10, the officials said. According to
ING, combined revenues from insurance premiums in 1999 would have
totaled $12.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ING agreed to pay $5.1 billion for ReliaStar's common stock and
assume $1 billion in ReliaStar's debt. The transaction, which
values ReliaStar at $54 per share, is expected to close late in the
third quarter of this year, subject to regulatory and ReliaStar
shareholder approval.
</P>
<P>
   ReliaStar's stock, which surged 43 percent on Friday amid rumors
of the impending deal, rose $7 per share to $51 in trading Monday
at 4:30 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Few job cuts are anticipated at ReliaStar's Minneapolis
headquarters or elsewhere, said John Turner, chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ReliaStar employs 3,800, including 1,500 in Minnesota, while ING
has about 90,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a limited number of positions that are related to
ReliaStar having been a public company that will disappear, but I
expect those people will be given opportunities in other areas
within the company,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition also could mean more jobs at ReliaStar's new
service center in Minot, N.D., he said. Employment at the center,
which opened six months ago, is expected to go beyond the 600
already targeted before the acquisition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ReliaStar, which had revenues of $3.04 billion in 1999, edging
into the Fortune 500 list of the nation's largest companies at No.
500, had been mentioned recently as a potential takeover target by
several possible suitors. ReliaStar officials felt ING was the best
fit, Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was not an auction process. It was a process that was
controlled by us,'' Turner said. ''ING has historically
demonstrated a high degree of concern for the interests of the
employees of the companies they merge with.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner declined to comment on what other companies had been
considered as partners.
</P>
<P>
   ReliaStar will continue its operations as part of ING Americas
and retain current management. Turner will become a member of the
executive committee at ING Americas and become vice chairman of the
Americas region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
