<HEADLINE> Minivan Accident Blamed on Motorist  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, N.C. (AP) -- An accident last month in which a
minivan lurched in reverse, killing an 11-year-old boy, happened
when the 84-year-old driver mistakenly hit the gas pedal instead of
the brake, the district attorney said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   No criminal charges will be filed against the driver, Sara Bell
Kennedy, in the March 22 crash at Smithfield Middle School,
District Attorney Tom Lock said. Lock said it was an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy had dropped off children at the school and put her
minivan into reverse when it raced backward and hit the children in
front of the school. Byrone Murray was killed and six others were
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no evidence to suggest that a mechanical defect or
malfunction caused or contributed to the collision. The accident
almost certainly was caused by driver error,'' Lock said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Lock said it appeared Kennedy touched the accelerator instead of
the brake pedal after backing a few feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''She probably panicked and overreacted by pressing even harder
on the gas pedal, believing it to be the brake pedal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lock said the state Highway Patrol reconstructed the accident
and interviewed more than two dozen witnesses. The van, a 1994
Dodge Caravan, was tested by an independent mechanical engineer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
