<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Shows His Lighter Side  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House was a little defensive -- and a
lot proud Monday of the video it presented last weekend in which
lame duck Bill Clinton joshed himself as being so underemployed he
had time to wash the presidential limo and run down the driveway
carrying a bag lunch for Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart captured the mood of
the president's aides: happy that the video was a smash but also on
guard against any suggestion that Clinton has so little to do that
he could spend unlimited time in taping sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing took two hours, said Lockhart. But another White
House official said earlier it was more like five or six hours.
</P>
<P>
   TV funnyman Jay Leno was impressed by Clinton's split-second
timing in his schtick Saturday night at the White House
Correspondents' Association annual black tie dinner -- Clinton's
eighth and last appearance as chief executive. The president did a
stand up comedy routine as well as starring in the video.
</P>
<P>
   Also impressed was Phil Rosenthal, creator and executive
producer of the sitcom ''Everybody Loves Raymond'' and producer of
the Clinton video.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was very willing and gracious ... and he did it with
enthusiasm and, I think, tremendous talent. Very, very funny. I
would say 90 percent of that was one take,'' Rosenthal said Monday
on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Leno, host of NBC's ''Tonight'' show, went so far to suggest
that Clinton might find post-presidential work as a comic.
</P>
<P>
   An example of Clinton's humor:
</P>
<P>
   ''The clock is running down on the Republicans in Congress, too.
I feel for them. I do. They've only got seven more months to
investigate me. That's a lot of pressure. So little time, so many
unanswered questions. For example, over the last few months I've
lost 10 pounds. Where did they go? Why haven't I produced them to
the Independent Counsel?''
</P>
<P>
   Or:
</P>
<P>
   ''(John) McCain as (George W.) Bush's running mate? Hasn't the
man suffered enough?'' Clinton joked, referring to McCain's years
as a POW during the Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
   The video showed a bored Clinton answering telephone calls,
mowing the lawn, trimming bushes, washing his limousine and
watching clothes spin in the dryer. In one scene he chases after
Hillary's car with the bag lunch he made for her.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, at a White House briefing
Monday, was asked if he was disappointed at being excluded from the
president's video.
</P>
<P>
   ''One always has things to aspire to in life,'' he deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had one more gag up its sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Allison Janney stepped to the White House podium Monday
and, for a minute or so, played the part of the president's press
secretary -- something she does in the NBC series, ''The West
Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no comment today but I will take questions,'' she
opened. She was barely getting warmed up when someone asked about
the acting abilities of the real Clinton spokesman, Lockhart, who
starred in a gag video Saturday night with cast members from ''The
West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Now hold on a second,'' Lockhart interrupted, cutting off
Janney's answer in mid sentence. He dismissed her with a quick,
''Thank you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
