<HEADLINE> Deal Keeps 'South Park' on Cable  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Cartman, Kyle, Kenny and the rest of the
twisted ''South Park'' crew will be on Comedy Central through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ''South Park'' creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone will come up
with at least 10 new episodes of the irreverent and oftentimes
bawdy cartoon series each year for three years under terms of a
deal struck Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The exclusive television and production development pact keeps
Parker and Stone at the cable channel through August 2003, Comedy
Central general manager Bill Hilary said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We look forward to continuing the wild ride that began with
'South Park' as we tap further into the artistic genius of this
extraordinarily creative team,'' Hilary said.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year contract, which goes into effect in September,
was described as a multimillion dollar deal, but financial details
weren't disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The pact calls for a minimum of 30 new episodes of ''South
Park,'' a new series to launch in 2001, ongoing series development
and a partnership agreement with Parker and Stone concerning the
syndication of ''South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   ''For the last three years we have been exceptionally lucky to
have our show on a network that respects creative freedom. We've
realized it is this freedom that has made us happiest, that's why
we've decided to stay with Comedy Central,'' Parker said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central, the only all-comedy network, is available in
over 63 million homes nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
