<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group chided for survey in N.J. has role in national seminar onteens  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A nonprofit research group that helped
organize Tuesday's White House Conference on Teen-agers has raised
the hackles of parents in some states for asking students detailed
questions about sexual activity and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Three parents are suing the Ridgewood, N.J., school district for
distributing the 156-question survey written by the Search
Institute of Minneapolis. The survey asks youths how many times
they have taken various illegal drugs, whether they have tried to
kill themselves, and what protection they use if they are sexually
active.
</P>
<P>
   The Radford, Va., school board refused to allow the survey to be
distributed in schools. Some Colorado Springs, Colo., parents
objected to the survey as intrusive. So did some parents in the
Middletown-Monroe school system in Ohio, who argued that questions
about sexual protection should not be asked of adults, much less of
children.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Benson, the institute's president, was among about a dozen
experts consulted by the White House in scheduling Tuesday's
conference on ''raising responsible and resourceful youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson will also speak at one of the afternoon sessions on the
subject, ''Closing the gap: How can we provide positive
opportunities for all teen-agers?''
</P>
<P>
   Benson said the vast majority of questions on the survey are
designed to measure positive influences in a given neighborhood.
The limited number of questions about sex and drugs, he said, are
there because ''these are the public health issues that have been
framed in America for 20 or 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Search Institute says more than 1 million students have
taken the survey over the past 10 years, and the vast majority of
communities have been happy with the results.
</P>
<P>
   ''The purpose of the survey is really to understand young
people's experiences of positive, healthy, productive things in
their communities, in their lives, in their schools,'' said Marc
Mannes, research director for the Search Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the direct questions about sex, Mannes said, ''Sexual
activity is something that young people are engaging in, and we're
trying to get honest and accurate information so communities can do
best by young people.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ridgewood, though, some parents were horrified that their
children were handed the survey in a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's one thing to take advantage of an adult, but it's another
thing to take advantage of a child in a public school environment,
a mandatory environment,'' said Frances Edwards, a mother of three
children in the Ridgewood school system. ''I find that insidious.
Their survey exploits the child, the (person) they say they are
trying to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1958, the Search Institute initially focused on
youths in religious settings. Though it still received money from
the Lutheran Brotherhood, the institute calls itself nonsectarian,
works primarily with public school districts and also received
money from the federal government, the Ford Foundation and such
corporate giants as Pillsbury and General Mills.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the questions in the controversial survey help the
institute pursue a program it calls ''asset-building.''
</P>
<P>
   Under that philosophy, children need 40 ''assets'' or strengths,
such as a B grade point average or better, caring neighbors and a
sense of integrity, to become productive adults.
</P>
<P>
   ''The primary message we give to communities is that these 40
building blocks are extremely important,'' Benson said. ''You know
it, scientists know it, and too few of the kids in your community
have these assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson said the institute has worked with 1,000 communities and
found objections in perhaps 10 of them. Usually, he said, ''People
say 'Oh, I see the larger purpose of this work.'''
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody in Ridgewood was convinced.
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of three families, the Rutherford Institute sued the
school district, charging that parents were not fully informed
about the survey before it was distributed to their children.
</P>
<P>
   Ridgewood school superintendent Frederick Stokley said parents
were given repeated notices throughout last year about the
forthcoming survey, including letters home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-01-00 1806 </TRAILER>
