<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court rejects New York dairy trade group's challenge  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- The U.S. Supreme Court made Carl
Peterson's day in the field a little brighter on Monday: The high
court put an end to a New York dairy trade group's challenge to a
compact that sets minimum prices for milk sold in New England.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, rejected the argument by New York
State Dairy Foods Inc. that the Northeast Dairy Compact
Commission's pricing plan discriminates against processors located
outside New England.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just confident that it (Supreme Court) was not going to
hear it because the lower court had a very strong ruling,'' said
Peterson, one of approximately 1,000 farmers in eastern New York
who sell milk to the compact. ''I'm not surprised, but I am
gratified.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, was Mae Schmidle, vice chair of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're extremely pleased with the outcome of this,'' she said.
''It certainly indicates the Northeast Dairy Compact is progressing
in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The compact was born in 1996, when Congress allowed
Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island, New Hampshire, Vermont
and Maine to group together to regulate milk prices in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The group sets minimum prices, which can be higher than the
price set by the federal government. Milk processors make payments
into a pool, and money from that pool is sent back to the
processors for distribution to the dairy farmers from whom they
bought milk.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Northeast plan, processors located in New England
receive rebates based on the total amount of milk they sell,
whether in the six-state region or elsewhere. Processors located
outside the region get rebates based on how much milk they sell in
New England in liquid form -- not milk for making into cheese, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge by New York State Dairy Foods began in 1997. The
trade group, which represents New York-based milk processors
Cumberland Farms, Crowley Foods, and Elmhurst Dairy, said dairy
farmers get a higher payback from New England processors and
therefore farmers prefer to do business with them.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Boston upheld the pricing rules, and the 1st
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed last November.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the trade group said they were dismayed by Monday's
ruling and vowed to pursue a political solution.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to oppose the unfair compact system through
legislative means here in New York state,'' Bruce Krupke, executive
vice president of New York Dairy Foods, Inc., said in a statement.
''We will also continue to try to enlighten our state's legislators
and dairy farmers on the negative impact the compact would have if
allowed to include New York state.'' He cited higher prices for
consumers as one of the negatives.
</P>
<P>
   New York, the third largest dairy producing state in the nation
behind California and Wisconsin, was denied admittance to the
compact last year after a bitter political battle broke out over
whether it should be abolished. The fight pitted the Northeast
against the Midwest, where there is widespread opposition to the
regional compacts.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, whose farm is located just west of Albany in Delanson,
said he wasn't sure what would happen if the compact was abolished
because prices are down so much, at their lowest in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been in business 49 years and my son wants to stay in
business,'' said Peterson, who took over the family farm from his
father in 1961. ''It's like a safety net when prices drop low. It
would make it very, very difficult because we're just surviving
right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-01-00 1826 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
