<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bergen County sheriff halts jail work, claiming big overruns  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos JAZ101-102.
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) -- Bergen County Sheriff Joseph L. Ciccone
on Monday halted work on the latest phase of a jail-expansion
project, asserting he wants answers on why it is 35 percent over
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The county's top official, Executive William ''Pat'' Schuber,
reacted by seeking a court injunction to end ''the sheriff's
political charade.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuber, a Republican, was elected to his third term in November
1998, when Ciccone, a Democrat, was elected sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   State Superior Court Judge Sybil R. Moses is to meet with both
sides at 11 a.m. Tuesday in her chambers at the Bergen County
Courthouse, where she is the presiding judge.
</P>
<P>
   The old county jail had been scheduled for demolition on Monday.
Ciccone said it would be cheaper to renovate the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Schuber said the project is only about 5 percent over budget,
and that Ciccone's unauthorized lockout is costing the county
$25,000 to $50,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the project was completed last month, and
inmates moved into new cells. When completed, the jail will be able
to accommodate 1,128 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The old jail held about 1,000, but some had to sleep on floors
and the crowding prompted lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   When conceived seven years ago, the two-part project was
budgeted at $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Record of Hackensack has calculated the overrun so far as
$16 million, a figure endorsed by Ciccone, according to his
spokesman, Bob Nesoff.
</P>
<P>
   Schuber said the project's true starting cost should be $53
million, which takes into account costs for mandated work that had
not been anticipated in the original estimate: construction of a
road entirely around the facility, removal of contaminated soil,
additions made by prior sheriffs, and a three-year delay due to
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The project will probably finish about 5 percent above that
figure, or about $55.7 million, Schuber said.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase includes a laundry and kitchen for inmates, and
what Nesoff termed ''plush office space'' and an amphitheater for
staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
