<HEADLINE> Bush Showing Slight Edge on Gore  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Al Gore
are locked in a close race for president, 49 percent for Bush to 44
percent for Gore, in a CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The five-point difference is within the poll's error margin of
plus or minus 5 percentage points for the 499 likely voters
surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Among registered voters, Bush had 46 percent, and Gore 45
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In this poll three weeks ago, Bush led 50 percent to 41 percent
among likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   In a four-way matchup with third-party candidates Pat Buchanan
and Ralph Nader, Bush had 47 percent and Gore 41 percent among
likely voters. Buchanan and Nader were at 4 points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was viewed favorably by six in 10, while Gore was viewed
favorably by just over half.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates were closely matched when people were asked
who was stronger on a number of personal qualities, but Bush was
favored on the question of strong and decisive leadership, CNN
reported Monday. Gore was slightly stronger on issues that are high
voter priorities like health care, while Bush was higher on crime.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 1,003 adults was taken Friday through Sunday and has
an error margin of 3 percentage points for the entire sample, 4
percentage points for registered voters and 5 percentage points for
likely voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
