<HEADLINE> Bonds Fall on Interest Rate Fears  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The price of 30-year Treasury bonds fell
modestly Monday, on interest rate fears and disappointment that the
Treasury won't increase its plans for paying down the U.S. debt.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark long-term Treasury fell ] point, or $3.75 per
$1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction, rose to 5.99 percent from 5.96 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term notes were weighed down by inflation concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists believe the robust economy is rekindling
inflation. Traders fear the Federal Reserve will be even more
aggressive in trying to cool of growth. That could mean raising
interest rates by one-half percentage point, rather than a
quarter-point increase that had been expected at a May 16 meeting
of the central bank's policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation and rising rates erode the value of investments that
pay a fixed return, such as bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Bond traders were also disappointed that when Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers said Monday that the Treasury intends to stick
with its previously announced plans for buying back U.S. debt.
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation that the Treasury would boost its
target for buying back debt. Previously, the Treasury has said it
will repurchase up to $30 billion in debt through the relatively
new buyback program.
</P>
<P>
   ''We plan to maintain our announced strategy with respect to
debt buybacks and the issuance of long-term debt,'' Summers said in
a statement released Monday afternoon. Summers was appearing at a
White House press conference to tout the administration's progress
on debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   The more bonds that are bought back the more the supply is
reduced, which would increase their value.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the price of short-term notes fell 3/32 point to 5/32
point, according to Bridge Telerate, a financial information
service. Intermediate maturities were down \ point to 7/16 point.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.98 percent as the
discount soared 0.17 percentage point from Friday to 5.82 percent.
Six-month yields were 6.24 percent as the discount rose 0.05 point
to 5.98 percent. One-year yields were 6.22 percent as the discount
rose 0.06 percentage point to 5.91 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, rose to 6.25 percent from 5.94 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 1/16 point to 94]. The average yield
rose to 6.04 percent from 6.00 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
