<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Names Platform Committee Chair  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush has put a staunch abortion foe,
Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, in charge of the platform committee
for the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment, announced Monday by the Republican National
Committee, suggests the party is unlikely to step away from its
blanket opposition to the procedure, a stance that prompted
dissension from GOP moderates before the 1996 convention in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Texas governor and presumed GOP presidential nominee,
opposes abortion except for in cases of rape, incest or when the
life of a mother is endangered.
</P>
<P>
   The platform has no such exceptions. The 1996 disagreement was
bridged when abortion rights supporters were allowed to add a
platform appendix.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Thompson is the senior Republican governor and an
articulate advocate of smaller, smarter government, greater freedom
and stronger families,'' RNC Chairman Jim Nicholson said. ''His
leadership and vision will be invaluable as our party crafts a
platform that reflects the hopes and ideas of Republicans and a
majority of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, first elected governor in 1986, said he looked forward
to ''serving on the committee to articulate our party's most
innovative ideas, the principles that bind us together and our
vision for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Thompson signed legislation outlawing a procedure
that opponents call ''partial-birth'' abortion. Bush has said he
would sign a similar nationwide ban if he is elected over Democrat
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's clear is that the Republican Party is going to continue
to play to its extreme elements that stand against a women's right
to choose,'' said Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway. ''Bush may say he's
a different kind of Republican, but obviously he clearly stands
behind the party platform on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer replied: ''The governor has full
faith in Tommy Thompson and his abilities to bring people
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Keane, a Thompson spokesman, said abortion is just one
issue the committee will digest.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what they like about Governor Thompson is that he's
always been someone to handle issues in a unified manner. You name
the issue and the governor has been out front on it and able to
bring people together on it,'' Keane said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Convention's Resolutions Committee, commonly
known as the platform committee, drafts the statement spelling out
the Republican Party's positions on an array of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Its membership consists of 107 delegates, including a male and
female delegate from each state and the District of Columbia, and
one each from the U.S. territories.
</P>
<P>
   Their resulting document must be approved by a majority of the
2,066 delegates at the convention, to be held July 31 to Aug. 3 in
Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
