<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Which Sonics Team Will Show?  </HEADLINE>
By LUIS CABRERA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- It's an ongoing game-day mystery for Seattle
SuperSonics coach Paul Westphal: Which team will show up against
the Utah Jazz?
</P>
<P>
   Will it be the Sonics who came out lifeless for two first-round
playoff pastings by the Jazz last week?
</P>
<P>
   Or will it be the team that was in command from the start of an
89-78 home victory Saturday that warded off a sweep and forced
Wednesday night's Game 4?
</P>
<P>
   ''This team has been up and down all year,'' Westphal said after
an intense, refereed practice Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can beat anybody, and we can lose to anybody,'' he said.
''Let's just hope the good guys come out Wednesday and we can beat
Utah.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz, back in Salt Lake City to prepare for Game 4, said
they knew the Sonics weren't going to roll over in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't do a lot of things, and they did everything,'' power
forward Karl Malone told The Deseret News. Malone scored 30 points
in the loss, following a dominating 50-point effort in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''They wanted it more; they got it,'' forward Bryon Russell said
of the loss.
</P>
<P>
   The victory came at ''desperation time, and Wednesday's going to
be the same,'' Sonics power forward Vin Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Key for Seattle will be the play of Rashard Lewis and a
re-energized Ruben Patterson, who made minimal contributions in
Games 1 and 2 but gave his teammates a lift off the bench in Game 3
with 13 points and crucial hustle plays.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 20, a 6-foot-10 forward who hits the 3 consistently
enough for Westphal to plug him in at guard on occasion, poses
matchup problems for 6-4 Jeff Hornacek and the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ''With me and Rashard in the game at the same time, that's a
real advantage for us,'' said Patterson, a 6-foot-6 small forward.
''I mean, who are they going to put Hornacek on? They can't put him
on me, and they damned sure can't put him on Rashard.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis hit two quick 3s to open Game 3, and finished with 14
points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said he's been impressed by the veteran-quality play of
Patterson, 22, and Lewis, both second-year players with no previous
playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''These guys aren't afraid,'' he said. ''Rashard has really
developed nicely. He goes out there and plays his game against
Utah. I guess he doesn't know he's not supposed to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said his confidence has grown as Westphal has increased
his minutes, and hitting the early jumpers helped.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm always going to be crashing the boards and getting the
rebounds, but if I'm hitting my jump shot, I'm going to have a good
game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said the home-crowd lift was huge Saturday after two games
in the hostile Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was the loudest crowd we've heard all year, and it helped
us. You saw it in Ruben and the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton took late command of the scrimmage Monday, barking
orders at teammates, motioning them inside or out, teaching on the
fly after botched plays. Payton, who didn't give interviews, had
spoken out after the two losses in Utah, saying the Sonics needed
him directing the offense at point guard instead of waiting on the
floor for an open shot.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal put Payton back at the point Saturday, and the All-Star
responded with 23 points, 10 assists and seven rebounds in 48
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a thing that was blown out of proportion to an
incredible extent,'' Westphal said Monday. ''We have some
competitive and even combative guys, and they don't like to lose.
If we go down, we're going to go down swinging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
