<HEADLINE> Senate Opens Debate on Education  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN, AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP)-- Democrats pushing for gun-control and new
teachers and Republicans touting voucher proposals and block grants
accused each other Monday of standing in the way of fixing
America's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's talk education reform,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., said as the Senate began rewriting the law governing
federal K-12 school aid. ''Let's not get distracted by all kinds of
non-relevant, extraneous topics.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat leaders promised Monday to offer amendments -- proposed
changes to the law -- that they said would bring the nation more
teachers, smaller classes and gun-free schools. Without those
plans, the Clinton administration said Monday, the bill would be
vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties will battle over giving states more freedom to
combine or transfer funds they get for such programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''A block grant cannot teach a child to read,'' said Sen. Patty
Murray, D-Wash. ''Let's invest in the things we know work. Smaller
classes, a good teacher ... those specific things can help teach a
child to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Republicans criticized Democrats for not supporting
school choice and steering away from the basics.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our students today are caught up in all kinds of studies of
minorities of one kind or another and fads of the day,'' said Sen.
Jon Kyl, R-Ariz. ''And they are not as well-educated about
traditional concepts.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate lawmakers planned to meet Tuesday to hash out compromises
on how many proposals could be offered for the Elementary and
Secondary Education Act, a 35-year-old law that expires this year.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrat Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota has said the
education bill school safety programs can provide a good
opportunity for the Senate to address gun-control. Measures such as
mandatory trigger-locks have languished in a juvenile justice bill
since last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, who can control the bill's fate, hasn't decided whether he
would try to block any gun-control proposals, said his spokesman
John Czwartacki.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're always searching for an agreement to try to get it
done,'' he said. ''Many would like to change it into a giant gun
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., who is helping manage the Senate's
work, said the Republicans are not out to limit floor debate:
''We're prepared for a lengthy debate with rational limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Any public discussion of education gives both parties a further
chance to tout their message on the popular election issue. Both
sides say Senate proposals in the coming weeks could mirror the
platforms assembled on the campaign trail by Vice President Gore
and Republican Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gov. Bush is not a defender of the status quo,'' Coverdell
said. ''His ideas are very much in concert with what is being
discussed here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 1950 </TRAILER>
