<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Working poor would get tax credit, under proposed bill  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Nearly 300,000 working families earning
$20,000 or less would get a state tax credit that could put as much
as $400 back into their pockets next year.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, A-40, passed the Assembly budget committee Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It expands the federal Earned Income Tax Credit to state
taxpayers and would be phased in over four years.
</P>
<P>
   In the first year, families earning $15,000 would get a check
from the state, ranging from $196 to $338. Those earning between
$15,000 and $20,000 would get a credit of between $114 and $229
that would offset their total tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   The amounts would increase each year until the program is fully
implemented in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, a bill sponsor, said the measure
would help working families who have trouble making ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the first piece of legislation that changes the income
tax structure in our state,'' Collins, R-Salem, said. ''When you're
working in New Jersey, we in the Legislature want to do what we can
to help, in any way we can.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first year of the program, families would receive 10
percent of the Earned Income Tax Credit they get from the federal
government for the 2000 tax year.
</P>
<P>
   That would increase to 15 percent in 2001, 17.5 percent in 2002
and 20 percent in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of the rebate depends on a family's income and size.
In the first year, a family with one child, earning $10,000 or less
would get a $238 check.
</P>
<P>
   When the program is fully implemented, families could get
anywhere from $238 to $823.
</P>
<P>
   Working poor families are also getting another break this year.
A new law, signed last year and also sponsored by Collins, raises
the threshold at which families have to pay state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   That threshold used to be $7,500. This year, anyone making
$15,000 or less doesn't have to pay state taxes. Next year, the
threshold will rise to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   That means that by tax year 2001, all families that qualify for
the state Earned Income Tax Credit would get a check from the
state, even though they paid no taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Ciro Scalera, director of the Association for Children of New
Jersey, said these two changes are helping to put New Jersey in the
forefront in helping the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Two years ago ... New Jersey ranked among the lowest of all
states'' when it came to helping working poor, Scalera said. ''New
Jersey will be moving from the lowest of states to much higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Others also applauded the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the type of program that helps people stand tall,''
said Marlene Lao-Collins, associate director of the New Jersey
Catholic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which Gov. Christie Whitman first proposed during
her budget address in January, would cost $48 million in the first
year, increasing to about $106 million after four years.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money would come from federal welfare funds. The
state has saved millions on welfare, thanks to plummeting welfare
rolls that most credit to the economy and tougher welfare laws.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Joseph Charles, D-Hudson, praised Collins' measure,
but asked that he consider ''friendly amendments.'' Those included
expanding the income eligibility to $30,000 -- the same as the
federal government allows.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to make the program available to single people and
childless couples, like the federal program does. And, he wants to
do away with the phase-in, giving people 20 percent of their
federal tax credit in the first year.
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblyman Paul DiGaetano, R-Passaic, a co-sponsor, said
Charles' version would cost too much, estimating the price tag to
be nearly $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Kornmehl, assistant state treasurer, said expanding the
income limits to $30,000 would cost about $24 million more
annually, once the program is fully implemented. He didn't know the
cost for giving the tax credit to single people and childless
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the current legislation provides a good starting
point and that it could be expanded later.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey would become the 12th state to offer a state tax
credit for the working poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-01-00 1950 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
