<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Remembers Holocaust Jews  </HEADLINE>
By JACK KATZENELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Flags were lowered to half-staff throughout
Israel Monday evening as Israelis remembered the six million Jews
murdered in the Nazi Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Israel marks the day, officially called Holocaust and Heroism
Memorial Day, in part by honoring those who resisted the Nazis.
Israelis grow up on stories of national heroism and still find it
difficult to digest the fact that most European Jews were helpless
before the Nazi death machine.
</P>
<P>
   For Israelis, the Holocaust is proof of the need for an
independent Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   The army's general staff held its weekly meeting at Lohamei
Hagetaot, a communal village in northern Israel founded by
survivors of the death camps and named after the Jews who revolted
against the Nazis in Warsaw and other eastern European cities.
</P>
<P>
   Army chief Lieut. Gen. Shaul Mofaz said holding the meeting at
Lohamei Hagetaot was ''a gesture of fighters to fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   At Yad Vashem, Israel's Holocaust Memorial, six Holocaust
survivors kindled flames in memory of the six million victims.
Survivors recalled how the Holocaust ripped families apart.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw my brother Moshe bending over a German and striking him
with an ax,'' said Kopel Kolpanitsky, 74, who survived an uprising
among Jews trapped in a ghetto in Lakhva, Belarus. ''I shouted,
'Moshe, get away!' But he made a gesture meaning, 'You get away.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kolpanitsky, then 16 years old, escaped into the forest, but his
mother, two brothers and sister were killed in the revolt, which
began after the Jews learned the ghetto was about to be liquidated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never saw my family again,'' Kolpanitsky said.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony was broadcast on a video screen at the ceremony as
he lit one of the six beacons.
</P>
<P>
   Movie houses, theaters and other places of entertainment were
closed, and radio and television stations broadcast somber music
and interviews with Holocaust survivors. Tuesday morning, a siren
will sound for one minute, and Israelis will literally stop in
their tracks to stand silently in memory of the victims. The
observance begins at sundown Monday and ends at sundown Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shevah Weiss, chairman of the Yad Vashem executive council, said
the day recalled ''sad and terrible memories of the darkest period
in the world's history.'' Weiss, himself a Holocaust survivor,
said: ''Europe became a lake of frozen Jewish blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak said the state of Israel is the
decisive answer to Hitler's scheme to ''wipe the name of Israel off
the face of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who lost relatives in the Holocaust, promised that
''never again will a Jew be a son without a home, and never again
will a Jew be defenseless.''
</P>
<P>
   A report released Monday expressed concern over Holocaust denial
and anti-Semitism on the Internet. Experts at Tel Aviv University
said the number of attacks throughout the world has dropped in the
past year, but their severity increased.
</P>
<P>
   Peace negotiations with the Palestinians in the southern Israeli
city of Eilat were suspended until the memorial day ends.
</P>
<P>
   ''We share with the Israeli people the feeling of pain and
sorrow on this day, a day of tragedy in Jewish history,'' said
senior Palestinian negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo. ''We hope that we
all learn the lesson of the necessity to end the days of tragedy
which both the Israeli and Palestinian peoples experienced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 2000 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000501.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reds-Pirates Game Postponed  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- This isn't the way the Pittsburgh Pirates
wanted to get Ken Griffey Jr. out.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds-Pirates game Monday night was rained out and will be
made up as part of a Sept. 8 twi-night doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle (2-0), the Reds' scheduled starter Monday, will
start Tuesday night in Philadelphia, with Steve Parris (1-3) moving
back a day to Wednesday and Pete Harnisch (0-3) starting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates left-hander Jimmy Anderson (1-0), who was to have
started Monday, was bumped from his start so Jason Schmidt (0-2)
can pitch Tuesday night in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt has been on the disabled list since April 19 with
inflammation in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll be fresh,'' Anderson said, who will go approximately 10
days between starts. ''I'll just go down to the bullpen and throw
harder than I normally would between starts. I don't like to miss a
start, but Jason needs to get out and pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his previous three starts when he threw as many as 137
pitches, Schmidt will be limited to about 85 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt last pitched on April 14, getting a no-decision in an
8-5, 12-inning loss to the New York Mets. In his other two starts,
he lost to the Astros 5-2 in the season opener and to Randy Johnson
and Arizona 1-0 on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to get him going,'' manager Gene Lamont said.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds rallied to win two of the final three games of the
abbreviated Pirates series, with Griffey's three-run homer leading
them to a 6-2 victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey continues to learn NL pitchers, and is still adjusting
to his new league, but has seven homers and 24 homers despite a
.217 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds are off to a less-than-brisk 12-12 start, but manager
Jack McKeon isn't disappointed. He agrees with Griffey that it
takes time for new players to blend into their surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a good club,'' McKeon said. ''We're just trying to
put everything together. A lot of clubs are trying to do that right
now. I like the way our starting pitching did the last time out,
and we've gotten pretty good production out of our bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds also started slowly last season, going 9-12 before
finishing 96-67.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a different ballclub than we had last year,'' McKeon
said. ''We've got some big hitters coming over here, and I don't
know this for a fact, but it seems like it takes a little while for
everybody to blend together. You go down the list, and we might
have 8-10 guys who weren't here last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It takes awhile for guys to get used to each other, to
understand what the other guy does, and develop camaraderie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates made a roster move, designating right-hander Brad
Clontz (0-0, 5.14 ERA in five appearances) for assignment to clear
a roster spot for Schmidt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 2002 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000501.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Hits GOP Spending  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Congress poised to begin writing
election-year spending bills, the Clinton administration is lashing
out at Republicans for choosing to emphasize tax cuts at the
expense of schools, veterans health care, debt reduction and other
programs.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to be delivered Tuesday, White House budget director
Jack Lew castigated Republicans for ''a bankrupt approach which
would lead either to misguided spending policies or undermine our
ability to pay down the debt.''
</P>
<P>
   A draft copy of Lew's address to the Urban Institute, obtained
by The Associated Press, laid down the administration's markers for
this year's budget fight. The White House wants a limited tax cut
and a focus on reducing the national debt, creating a new
prescription drug benefit for Medicare recipients, expanding health
coverage for low-income Americans and providing more money for
schools, technology and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''By passing an oversized tax scheme, Congress has effectively
made the decision that tax cuts are more important than any of the
other choices that might be made,'' Lew said in his prepared
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   And signaling that the White House is comfortable pitting GOP
tax cut plans against politically popular debt reduction, Lew
asked, ''Will we plan ahead with realism and responsibility or
simply live for the moment, hoping that everything will be just
fine in the future?''
</P>
<P>
   This week, subcommittees of the House and Senate Appropriations
committees plan to write the first of the 13 annual spending bills
for the coming fiscal year. GOP leaders hope to complete the
measures by early fall -- without a major showdown with President
Clinton -- so lawmakers can go home early and campaign for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   On April 14, Congress approved a GOP-written $1.83 trillion
budget for fiscal 2001, which begins Oct. 1. It called for a
five-year tax cut of at least $150 billion and perhaps more than
$200 billion, depending on lawmakers' future decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The spending blueprint reserved the entire Social Security
surplus, projected at nearly $1 trillion through 2005, for debt
reduction. It also called for increases for some education,
veterans and other programs, and set aside up to $40 billion for
prescription benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Final decisions on tax and spending will be made as Congress
begins working seriously on such bills. But for now, Republicans
say their plans are a sound division of federal resources.
</P>
<P>
   John Feehery, spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., said Lew's speech reflects ''the insatiable need of the
White House to spend more money.'' He said the administration is
trying to ''paint us as extremists when they know we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The speaker has provided balanced leadership and it drives
Jack Lew nuts,'' Feehery said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
