<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workers Strike Ohio State Univ.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- About 1,900 janitors, drivers and other
workers at Ohio State University went on strike Monday, disrupting
trash pickup, meals and bus service on the 48,000-student campus.
</P>
<P>
   Some professors canceled classes or held them outdoors so
students would not have to cross picket lines. But campus life
seemed close to normal for many others.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between the university and Local 4501 of the
Communications Workers of America broke down early Monday, and no
further talks were scheduled. The previous three-year contract
expired March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The workers average about $10 an hour and want an immediate
$2-an-hour raise.
</P>
<P>
   The university has offered $1 an hour for the year beginning
July 1 for skilled trade and service workers and 50 cents an hour
in each of the following two years.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Josephson, president of the union local, said workers are
prepared to strike ''until we have fair and equitable solutions for
our members.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State President William Kirwan said ''it is in the
university's interest to have a fair, equitable and competitive
salary structure.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have no intention of letting this drag out,'' Kirwan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
