<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Said Taking Toll on Tanzania  </HEADLINE>
By RODRIQUE NGOWI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) -- President Benjamin Mkapa said
Monday that AIDS is taking a heavy toll on Tanzania's economy as
large numbers of the country's trained work force are succumbing to
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some ministries lose about 20 employees each month to AIDS,
and 365 workers of the Tanzania Electric Supply Company died
between 1995 and April this year,'' Mkapa said in an address
marking May Day.
</P>
<P>
   He said the hardest-hit ministries including defense, education
and health.
</P>
<P>
   Mkapa's remarks came as the Clinton administration in Washington
defended its decision to qualify the worldwide increase in AIDS
cases as a threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Thurman, director of the White House Office of National
AIDS Policy, said AIDS has become such an epidemic that, in years
to come, it threatens to destabilize nations and the economies of
whole continents.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to respond to this because we've never seen a crisis
like HIV and AIDS globally,'' Thurman said. ''We're beginning to
understand that this epidemic, not only has health implications,
but has implications as a fundamental development issue, an
economic issue and a stability and security issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank projects that Tanzania's gross domestic product
will decline by between 15 and 25 percent by 2015 if AIDS continues
to spread at the current rate.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, between 15 to 30 percent of the members
of Tanzania's armed forces are infected with HIV, the virus that
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Mkapa sought to win support from hardline
Christian and Islamic leaders opposed to public discussion of
sexuality and AIDS-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I pray that religious leaders consider the stark reality in
the light of the current situation and the given statistics,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of AIDS nationwide featured prominently in rallies
marking May Day in both mainland Tanzania and the semiautonomous
region of Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers estimate that about 20 percent of Tanzania's 33.3
milllion people are HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are similar in Kenya and Uganda, Tanzania's
neighbors on the East African Cooperation, a regional economic
grouping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 2018 </TRAILER>
