<HEADLINE> Miami Mayor, Manager Continue Battle  </HEADLINE>
By MEG RICHARDS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- On the same day the mayor accused him of extortion,
the embattled city manager on Monday named a new police chief to
replace the previous leader who resigned after fallout from the
Elian Gonzalez raid.
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Donald Warshaw appointed Raul Martinez, a 24-year
veteran of the Miami Police Department and a former assistant
chief. Martinez becomes the first Hispanic to hold the position in
the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two years, Martinez, 50, has been an assistant city
manager, overseeing the parks and public works departments. As a
police officer, he headed internal affairs and worked in
intelligence and community policing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I pledge to all of you, to be the chief of police for the
entire community,'' said Martinez, who was born in Cuba and came to
the United States when he was 12. ''I ask that we put away our
differences and look at all the common things that we have, and
make this city a great city.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's hiring comes as the fallout from the April 22 federal
raid and the way police handled protesters has swelled into a
struggle between Miami Mayor Joe Carollo and Warshaw.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo, angered that Police Chief William O'Brien had not
notified him when federal agents told him that they were headed to
the home of Elian's relatives, demanded that Warshaw fire him.
Warshaw refused.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, the mayor had fired the city manager and O'Brien had
resigned, saying that Carollo was too divisive.
</P>
<P>
   However under the city charter, Warshaw's firing can't take
effect for 10 days, which would be Sunday. The charter also
specifies that the city manager names the police chief, with no
requirement the mayor be consulted.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's appointment as chief comes on the same day Carollo
made allegations that Warshaw blackmailed him. Carollo also
launched an investigation into allegations Warshaw misused city
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''The city manager sent an extortion demand to me that if I
fired him he would take me out as mayor. ... would file criminal
charges against me ... (and) I would lose my pension,'' Carollo
said. ''No city manager should be allowed to extort a mayor in any
city in America.''
</P>
<P>
   While police chief, Carollo said Warshaw charged personal
expenses to an American Express card and used a youth group's
office at the police department as the billing address.
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw has said none of the organization's money was used to
pay his bills.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a blackmailer. I'm not an extortionist. I'm not really
sure where the mayor was going with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 2025 </TRAILER>
