<HEADLINE> $22M Donated For Journalism School  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The University of Oklahoma will use a $22
million donation from publisher Edward L. Gaylord and his family to
build a college of journalism and mass communication.
</P>
<P>
   The donation includes $14 million for the construction of
Gaylord Hall at the university in Norman, 25 miles from Oklahoma
City, and a $8 million endowment to fund faculty positions and
student scholarship and internships.
</P>
<P>
   ''This extraordinary gift will assure the University of Oklahoma
a place among the leading U.S. institutions engaged in journalism
and media education,'' Oklahoma University President David Boren
said.
</P>
<P>
   Edward L. Gaylord is the editor and publisher of The Oklahoman.
The donation was announced in Sunday's editions of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The university's journalism and mass communication program will
be elevated from school to college status. There are about 700
undergraduate students and 30 graduate students in the program.
</P>
<P>
   The donation is the largest single gift to a public university
in state history.
</P>
</TEXT>
