<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart Sues in Medicaid Case  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES JEFFERSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc. filed a federal lawsuit
Monday to bar the state of Arkansas from paying large drug store
chains less than smaller stores for filling Medicaid prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest retailer seeks to block the state from
following a two-tiered reimbursement policy that reduces payments
to chains that operate 11 or more stores in the state. The
Bentonville-based company said the lawsuit was filed with the
federal court at Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   The policy is discriminatory and violates the equal protection
clause of the 14th Amendment, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Human Services, which oversees the
Medicaid program providing health services for the poor, elderly
and disabled, implemented the new policy Friday after several
delays.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Hanley, the DHS medical services director, said the agency
had authority from the federal Health Care Financing Administration
to start the plan March 1. The agency went ahead with the policy
Friday after the pharmacy industry failed to offer long-promised
cost-saving alternatives, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart spokesman Jay Allen said the state offered no rational
basis for discriminating against larger pharmacy chains. DHS
officials ignored Wal-Mart's proposal to accept the lowest rate any
pharmacy in the state accepts for a Medicaid prescription, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state is the largest Medicaid customer and they want the
lowest possible rate. We are willing to do that,'' Allen said.
''Our only request and requirement is that all pharmacies in the
state be treated equally.''
</P>
<P>
   Rex Nelson, a spokesman for Gov. Mike Huckabee, said, ''We feel
we are on very solid legal ground in trying to get the taxpayers of
Arkansas the best deal possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said the lawsuit was the company's last resort after six
months of negotiations failed to produce an agreement. He said
Wal-Mart would not pass along to customers what it says is an
average loss of $4 per Medicaid prescription under the state's new
reimbursement plan.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley put the change at about $2.50 per prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart operates pharmacies at 86 of its stores in the state.
Allen said Wal-Mart is the largest provider of Medicaid
prescriptions in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1999, he said, the company's average price for
Medicaid prescriptions was $6.65 less than the average prescription
price of other pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're biting the hand that is saving them literally millions
of dollars annually,'' Allen said. ''We have encouraged and offered
to help the state deal with the long-term issue here -- rising
medical costs. They have shown no interest in that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanley said Wal-Mart could afford to charge less because its
Medicaid clientele is generally ambulatory and children needing
lower-cost generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The company does not provide the more costly drugs and services
that small independents do, he said, such as delivery, charge
accounts, 24-hour service and no nursing homes business or service
for AIDS and mental health patients needing higher-cost drugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
