<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Time Warner Pulls Plug on Disney in Key Markets
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission plans to hold
negotiations tonight with the Walt Disney Co. and Time Warner after the cable
giant pulled the plug on ABC programming. Disney, ABC's corporate parent, is
fighting over how much money Time Warner must compensate Disney for the right to
carry some of its cable channels. Disney had offered a series of deadline
extensions after the original national transmission deal expired Dec. 31. The
most recent deadline, offered in March, expired at 12:01 a.m. on Monday, when
ABC was blacked out in the homes of 3.5 million Time Warner cable customers in
the New York City area, Houston and Raleigh-Durham, N.C.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House E-mail Furor Rages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House is raising the possibility it may invoke
executive privilege to keep Congress from seeing some documents in the furor
over missing e-mails under subpoena in investigations ranging from Whitewater to
impeachment, documents disclosed today. The White House sent the House
Government Reform Committee a one-page list of documents it is not turning over
under subpoena because of executive privilege and attorney-client
confidentiality. Among documents on the list, which was obtained by The
Associated Press, are notes by White House lawyers involving discussions they
had with computer experts about the e-mails.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll Shows Gore Slightly Trailing Bush
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Al Gore are locked
in a close race for president, 49 percent for Bush to 44 percent for Gore, in a
new CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll. The five-point difference is within the poll's
error margin of plus or minus 5 percentage points for the 499 likely voters
surveyed. Among registered voters, Bush had 46 percent, and Gore 45 percent. In
a four-way matchup with third-party candidates Pat Buchanan and Ralph Nader,
Bush had 47 percent and Gore 41 percent among likely voters. Buchanan and Nader
were at 4 points apiece.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Expects Palestinian State
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EILAT, Israel (AP) -- Israeli officials said Monday they've resigned
themselves to Palestinian statehood. But Mideast peace negotiators reported
little progress and awaited the arrival of a U.S. mediator Tuesday to help draft
an outline of a final peace treaty. Israeli officials said they would not oppose
a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, but said the Palestinians
should accept that some Jewish settlements there will become part of Israel.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Canada Suspends Ties With Vietnam
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Canada suspended government contacts with Vietnam today and
delayed annual meetings on development aid to protest the execution of a
Canadian woman convicted of drug smuggling. Nguyen Thi Hiep and her mother were
arrested in 1996 after custom's officers at the Hanoi airport found 12 pounds of
heroin hidden in art work. Nguyen was sentenced to death, while her mother
received life imprisonment. Canadian authorities asked Vietnam to delay the
execution because of evidence the women were duped by drug smugglers into
transporting the heroin. But the execution proceeded without prior announcement
last week.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Actors Strike TV, Radio Commercials
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Actors who star in TV and radio commercials went on
strike today, demanding a bigger cut from the booming cable market, in the first
major Hollywood walkout in 12 years. Hundreds gathered in a Los Angeles park and
marched past Wilshire Boulevard ad agencies. Several hundred striking actors
also rallied in New York City. The Screen Actors Guild and the American
Federation of Television &AMP; Radio Artists, representing about 135,000 actors,
authorized the strike. Celebrities lent support to the commercial actors on both
coasts. ''Actors are the nicest people in the world, and they always give away
the store,'' Richard Dreyfuss said at a rally in New York.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 77; Nasdaq Rises 97
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors brushed off worries about Microsoft's future
today, sending its shares higher and fueling a rally in technology stocks that
boosted the stock market. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 77.87 to end at
10,811.78. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,959-1,055. The Nasdaq rose 97.42 to
3,958.08. Microsoft rose 3 11/16 to 73 7/16.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Baseball Sets One-Month HR Mark
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Batters hit 931 homers, a major league record for one month
and 140 more than last April, according to the Elias Sports Bureau, baseball's
official statistician. Not including the four hit in March during the Mets-Cubs
series in Japan, there's been an average of 2.55 homers per game, up 13 percent
from the average of 2.25 last April.
</P>
