<HEADLINE> Chiapas Bishop Pushes for Peace  </HEADLINE>
By ALEJANDRO RUIZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- The new bishop for
Chiapas state took over Monday, saying there will be no peace in
the troubled region as long as serious injustices persist.
</P>
<P>
   But Bishop Felipe Arizmendi Esquivel made it clear during his
inaugural Mass attended by thousands of Roman Catholics in this
colonial city that he does not support violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''There cannot be true and lasting peace as long as there are
serious injustices and exclusion. But guns only provoke more
poverty and misery,'' Arizmendi said. ''Jesus Christ does not
accept resorting to violent methods.''
</P>
<P>
   His predecessor, Bishop Samuel Ruiz became known among
supporters as the ''bishop of the poor'' for his work with
poverty-stricken Indian peasants. But the government and
conservatives criticized Ruiz, linking him with leftist Zapatista
National Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's southernmost and poorest state has become increasingly
polarized since the Zapatistas began a short-lived rebellion six
years ago, seeking greater rights for Indians. Sporadic peace talks
are at a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi, formerly the bishop of Tapachula on the Chiapas
coast, is known as a moderate with some conservative positions. He
has sharply criticized the Zapatistas for choosing to wage an armed
rebellion. Nonetheless, he also has supported Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi on Monday called for reconciliation -- asking the army
to respect human rights, and the rebels and the government to make
an effort to advance peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chiapas is hungry and thirsty for peace,'' Arizmendi said.
''No more war, because no reason or person is superior to another.
It is time for reconciliation and brotherhood.''
</P>
<P>
   A tearful Ruiz, who said goodbye to the parishioners one by one,
expressed confidence that Arizmendi would continue his pastoral
work in the indigenous communities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no doubt that the work of the diocese will not only
continue, but will keep leading the way toward challenging and
resolving the conflicts that arise along the path of this
diocese,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
