<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was higher against the yen early Tuesday
on signs the American economy is still going strong. Tokyo stocks
rose following Wall Street's rally.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 108.66 yen, up 0.68 yen from late Monday but
below its late New York level of 108.79 yen. The New York quote was
the dollar's highest level since March 1, when the currency bought
110.31 yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average climbed 150.95
points, or 0.82 percent, to 18,554.03 points in the first 30
minutes of trading. On Monday, the average closed up 429.38 points,
or 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar's firmness remained intact on
the back of strength in U.S. financial markets and continued
strength in the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Purchasing Management said Monday
that the U.S. manufacturing sector registered further growth in
April, and the government reported separately on a surprising rise
in construction spending in March.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 99.55 yen, up from
98.56 yen late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, prices continued to rise in line with gains
in New York stocks and higher futures prices in Monday's Chicago
Mercantile Exchange. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 77.87
points to close at 10,811.78 on Monday. The technology-heavy Nasdaq
composite index rose 97.42 to close at 3,958.08.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 15.24 points, or 0.90 percent, to 1,710.47
points. The TOPIX closed up 46.36 points, or 2.8 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.7450 percent from Monday's finish of 1.7350 percent. Its price
fell 0.08 point to 100.47.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
