<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Rebels Urged To Cease-Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Monday
urged southern Sudanese rebels to join a renewed cease-fire so U.N.
agencies and charities can safely deliver food and medicine to
hundreds of thousands of embattled villagers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sudanese government agreed to renew, for three months, a
cease-fire that expired April 15. The accord came after a meeting
between on Saturday Foreign Minister Mustafa Osman Ismail and
Mohammed Saliheen, the head of the U.N. World Food Program in
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army has yet to say whether
it will join the cease-fire, but Annan, who is on a tour of Africa,
said he hoped they will ''contribute to the creation of an enabling
environment for humanitarian operations.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Secretary-General counts on the continued support of all
parties for the unhindered and safe provision by U.N. humanitarian
agencies and non-governmental organizations of relief to all those
in need of humanitarian aid throughout the country,'' spokesman
David Wimhurst said in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The truce, however, has been routinely violated by both
government and rebel forces, with each side blaming the other.
</P>
<P>
   After Sudan obtained independence from Britain in 1956, a civil
war erupted, mainly over the degree of autonomy for the largely
Christian and animist south from the Muslim, Arab north. A shaky
peace reached in 1972 broke down in 1983, and an estimated 2
million people have since died as a result of fighting and
war-induced famine.
</P>
<P>
   The SPLA draws its support from among some 1.7 million Christian
and animist people of the south.
</P>
<P>
   The World Food Program warned last week that its aid supplies
would run out by June, leaving about 2 million people in danger of
starvation. The agency appealed for increased aid, saying that it
had received only a fraction of the amount it asked for in January.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels reportedly blew up Sudan's only oil pipeline on Monday,
state television reported.
</P>
<P>
   The blast at Singat, 30 miles east of the capital Khartoum,
severely damaged the 1,000 mile pipeline from the Higlig oil field
to the Red Sea, causing a temporary halt to the flow, the
television said in its evening newscast.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline, which is capable of pumping some 150,000 barrels
of crude oil a day, is an important source of revenue for Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The bulletin said security officials found leaflets at the scene
signed by a group called the Beja Conference, which is made up of
four eastern tribes who are fighting for autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   The report could not be independently verified and there was no
immediate claim of responsibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
