<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sahara Parties To Join Conference  </HEADLINE>
By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- A top U.N. envoy has invited the key
players in the dispute over Western Sahara to a conference in
London this month in hopes of breaking the territory's decades-long
political crisis, diplomats said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   James Baker III, the former American secretary of state, is
hoping for a political settlement to the lingering post-colonial
dispute not that new leaders are place in Algeria and Morocco, the
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco and Mauritania both claimed Western Sahara in 1976 after
Spain abandoned the northwest African territory. Morocco then
annexed the area and moved in settlers.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel Polisario Front launched a guerrilla war for
independence that ended in 1991 with a U.N.-negotiated cease-fire
and an agreement to hold a referendum on independence or
integration with Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum has stalled for years, chiefly over the issue of
voter eligibility. In a February report, U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said he doubted the referendum could be held as planned.
</P>
<P>
   After a visit to Africa in April, Baker returned convinced the
U.N. plan for Western Sahara was stuck.
</P>
<P>
   ''The settlement plan is not dead, it is very much still alive
but it is in the ditch. It is in trouble and it is in rather big
trouble,'' Baker said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to salvage the plan or devise an alternative, Baker
last week issued invitations to the four key players -- Morocco,
Mauritania, Polisario and Algeria, which has backed the rebels -- to
come to London beginning May 14 for a new round of talks, diplomats
said.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco is now ruled by King Mohammed VI, who ascended to the
throne last July on the death of his father, King Hassan II.
Algeria elected Abdelaziz Bouteflika president in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The two men recently held the first meeting between their
countries' leaders in nearly 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
