<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special Ed Case Focused On Progress  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN, AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Baltimore Public Schools and lawyers for
special education students suing the district agreed Monday to
streamline a laundry list of demands, bringing a 16-year-old
lawsuit closer to an end.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which focuses less on paperwork and more on
measurable results such as test scores and graduation rates, offers
the best hope to date of ending the dispute, said federal appeals
Judge David Tatel, who mediated what he called a final step toward
resolving the 1984 lawsuit over the lack of resources for special
education students.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each side compromised in the interest of improving
education,'' said Tatel, of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for
the District of Columbia. ''They got the court's message loud and
clear that they were not going to make commitments they could not
fulfill.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatel presented this latest agreement to U.S. District Judge
Marvin J. Garbis, who signed it Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement does not drop the lawsuit -- one of the longest of
several such class-action cases nationwide. Rather, it gives the
district and state education officials up to three years to meet
goals that could release them from a previous court order.
</P>
<P>
   Those goals include raising special-needs students' test scores,
ensuring more of them are educated in regular classrooms and
graduate from high school.
</P>
<P>
   ''The proof will be in the classroom,'' said Steven Ney, legal
director of the Maryland Disability Law Center, which brought the
lawsuit. ''This is clearly a major step in the case. It makes the
lawsuit a little simpler and more well-defined.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendants, which also include the city, school board and
the state of Maryland, said Monday they struggled for years to
please the plaintiffs. The plan pared 41 goals down to 14,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   This agreement is the first realistic request of a school system
that is struggling to help all of its students, said Carol Ann
Baglin, who oversees special education for the state of Maryland.
The state must help the district meet some of the goals.
</P>
<P>
   Jodi French, a Baltimore school system official, said in an
interview these new goals could help struggling districts like
Baltimore focus on the complex federal special education law. The
1975 Individuals with Disabilities Education Act gives states money
to help end discrimination against disabled children.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before, we just had concepts,'' French said.
</P>
<P>
   The goals -- with two- to three-year timelines -- include:
</P>
<P>
   --Raising special education students' graduation rates from 32
percent to 41.6 percent;
</P>
<P>
   --Ensuring 58.8 percent of special education pupils are
''mainstreamed,'' or educated in regular classrooms;
</P>
<P>
   --Keeping 80 percent of newly identified special-needs students
in their community schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 2148 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
