<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> June Set For Burundi Peace Accord  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHE NKURUNZIZA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) -- President Pierre Buyoya on Monday gave
his clearest support yet to ending Burundi's seven-year civil war,
saying a power-sharing agreement with Hutu rebels and political
parties would be completed in June.
</P>
<P>
   ''The road to peace is open. There will be no winners and no
losers. All Burundians will triumph,'' Buyoya told thousands of
people gathered at the capital's Rwagasore stadium to mark Labor
Day celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya said former South African President Nelson Mandela,
mediator of the peace talks, will meet with Hutu rebel leaders in
South Africa next week to make sure they attend the next round of
negotiations in the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next two weeks, a committee will present a draft
peace agreement to the 19 political parties and interested groups,
Buyoya said.
</P>
<P>
   Although not yet formalized, the agreement centers on a
transitional government; the integration of Hutu rebels into the
Tutsi-dominated army and an electoral system that will ensure power
sharing between the minority Tutsis and majority Hutus.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people have died in Burundi's civil war since
October 1993, when Tutsi paratroopers assassinated Melchior
Ndadaye, a Hutu who won the country's first democratic elections.
The vote spread panic among some Tutsis who had been in control of
the army, government and economy since independence in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   From November 1993 to July 1996, a coalition government made up
of Tutsis and Hutus ruled the country.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya, a retired Tutsi major, came to power in a July 1996 coup
that toppled the largely ineffective government.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya promised that the agreement will make it possible for
more than 1 million Burundians who are either displaced in camps
inside the country or in refugee camps in neighboring Tanzania to
return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Arusha negotiations began in July 1998. Last year, Mandela
replaced late Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere as mediator and
invited all the Hutu rebel groups that had been previously excluded
to take part in the peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
