<HEADLINE> Cut in Calif. Park Fees Suggested  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HARRIGAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) -- Seizing on next year's huge state
budget surplus, Gov. Gray Davis on Monday proposed cutting entrance
fees in half at most of the 265 state parks, beaches and museums.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the Legislature, the move would reverse a series
of three fee increases during the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of this wondrous economy, we have been blessed with
additional resources,'' Davis, a Democrat, said during a news
conference at Tapia State Park, in the Santa Monica Mountains
northwest of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the state general fund would make up for the $30
million estimated to be lost from the fees each year, Davis said.
That's just a fraction of next year's expected state budget
surplus, estimated at $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed fee cuts would begin July 1. Under the plan, the
daily fee to use a state park would be cut from $5 to $6 per
vehicle to $2 to $3 per vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 million Californians and tourists use the parks each
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
