<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Search for Deadly Pet Disruptes Toronto
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A full-scale search for a deadly pet snake had
all the trappings of a crime scene Monday, as police cordoned off
parts of a downtown neighborhood with yellow tape and officials
staged a stakeout of homes and shops.
</P>
<P>
   The aggressive approach paid off when the search team discovered
the 45-centimetre saw-scaled viper coming out from under a radiator
in its owner's home late Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The viper was one of up to 20 snakes kept in an apartment above
a strip of shops in a busy shopping and residential district of the
city's west end.
</P>
<P>
   Its owner reported the reptile missing after realizing it hadn't
been in its cage for three days.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed because a single bite from the reptile can kill,
everyone from police to firefighters and ambulance crews had
descended on the area called Parkdale, shutting down stores and
warning schools and day-care centers to keep children indoors.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Alberta Government Moves To Cut Off Debate on Private Health Bill
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Alberta's controversial private-health
bill -- being watched across Canada for its potential to change the
face of medicare -- is one step closer to becoming law.
</P>
<P>
   Premier Ralph Klein's Conservative government served notice
Monday it will unilaterally shut down debate -- to thwart opposition
stalling tactics -- and move Bill 11 into third and final reading.
</P>
<P>
   That move could come as early as today.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's been a tremendous amount of debate on this bill to
date,'' said Klein. ''At some time you have to have a vote. That's
the democratic process.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the bill is expected to pass third reading within two
weeks. Then, Klein said, after it has received royal assent by
Lt.-Gov. Lois Hole and regulations are written up, the goal would
be for cabinet to give its final OK -- called proclamation -- by the
fall to make it the law of the province.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Peschisolido Withdraws From Alliance Race, Endorses Long
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Toronto lawyer Joe Peschisolido abandoned his
low-profile campaign to lead the Canadian Alliance on Monday and
threw his support behind rival Tom Long.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement is good news for Long, who's selling himself as
the Alliance's best hope in Ontario, where the fledgling party
desperately needs a breakthrough in the next federal election.
</P>
<P>
   Peschisolido broke with his own advisers, who are endorsing
former Alberta treasurer Stockwell Day.
</P>
<P>
   Long is a key strategist for Ontario Conservatives who helped
Premier Mike Harris win two elections.
</P>
<P>
   Peschisolido has hardly said a word since January when he
announced his bid to lead the Alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
