<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Castro Leads May Day March for Elian
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Fidel Castro took an active role in May Day festivities for
the first time in years today, marching in the parade and ending a speech with a
cell phone call to Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who is fighting to bring his refugee
son, Elian, home to Cuba from the United States. The 73-year-old Cuban leader
who has ruled for 41 years guided a sea of chanting, flag-waving men, women and
children from Havana's sprawling Plaza of the Revolution to the U.S. Interests
Section almost two miles away.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
May Day Rallies Create Tensions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Anti-capitalist demonstrators clashed with police Monday in
central London, daubing anti-war slogans on the Cenotaph war memorial, tearing
down the golden arches of a McDonald's and spray-painting a hammer and sickle on
a statue of Winston Churchill in a May Day protest. Prime Minister Tony Blair
decried the demonstrators, saying, ''The people responsible for the damage
caused in London today are an absolute disgrace.'' He added, ''To deface the
Cenotaph and the statue of Winston Churchill is simply beneath contempt. It is
only because of the bravery and courage of our war dead that these idiots can
live in a free country at all.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Time Warner Yanks Plug on ABC
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission planned to hold
negotiations tonight with the Walt Disney Co. and Time Warner after the cable
giant pulled the plug on ABC programming. Disney, ABC's corporate parent, is
fighting over how much money Time Warner must compensate Disney for the right to
carry some of its cable channels. Disney had offered a series of deadline
extensions after the original national transmission deal expired Dec. 31. The
most recent deadline expired at 12:01 a.m. on Monday, when ABC was blacked out
in the homes of 3.5 million Time Warner cable customers in the New York City
area, Houston and Raleigh-Durham, N.C., and elsewhere.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Haider Quits As Freedom Party Chief
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Joerg Haider officially resigned Monday as head of
his far-right party in the same way he's led it for the past 14 years -- with a
speech lashing out at his critics. In a 90-minute speech to the Freedom Party
congress, Haider, 50, said that his decision to step down was a necessity and
called for unity. The meeting came after several months of international and
domestic protest against the Freedom Party's inclusion in the Austrian
government. Haider gained notoriety for praising the ''orderly'' full employment
policies of Adolf Hitler, and calling Waffen SS veterans ''men of honor.'' He
has repeatedly apologized for such remarks.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Canada Protests Vietnam Execution
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Canada suspended government contacts with Vietnam today and
delayed annual meetings on development aid to protest the execution of a
Canadian woman convicted of drug smuggling. Nguyen Thi Hiep and her mother were
arrested in 1996 after custom's officers at the Hanoi airport found 12 pounds of
heroin hidden in art work. Nguyen was sentenced to death, while her mother
received life imprisonment. Canadian authorities asked Vietnam to delay the
execution because of evidence the women were duped by drug smugglers into
transporting the heroin. But the execution proceeded without prior announcement
last week.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Actors Stage Walkout Over Ad Pay
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Actors who star in TV and radio commercials went on
strike today, demanding a bigger cut from the booming cable market, in the first
major Hollywood walkout in 12 years. Hundreds gathered in a Los Angeles park and
marched past Wilshire Boulevard ad agencies. Several hundred striking actors
also rallied in New York City. The Screen Actors Guild and the American
Federation of Television &AMP; Radio Artists, representing about 135,000 actors,
authorized the strike.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average on Tuesday climbed 150.95 points to
18,554.03 in early trading, rising in line with gains in New York stocks and
higher futures prices in Chicago Mercantile Exchange. The Dow Jones industrial
average rose 77.87 points to close at 10,811.78 on Monday. The technology-heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 97.42 to close at 3,958.08.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
76ers Sting Hornets 105-99
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHIILADELPHIA (AP) -- Aaron McKie, starting in place of the injured Eric
Snow, hit four consecutive 3-pointers and scored 13 straight points midway
through the fourth quarter as the Philadelphia 76ers beat the Charlotte Hornets
105-99 tonight to win their first-round series 3-1. Philadelphia plays the
winner of the Milwaukee-Indiana series in the Eastern Conference semifinals.
McKie scored a career playoff high 25 points and had 11 assists. Allen Iverson,
playing with a chip fracture in his right ankle and an inflamed right elbow,
scored 26.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON
</SUBHEAD>
