<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Counters Tabloid Criticism  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Prime Minister Tony Blair took the time to send
The Sun tabloid a handwritten reply to pointed criticism of his
first three years in office.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Sun, in saying we have done nothing in three years in
government apart from create a strong economy, is more than a
little unfair,'' Blair wrote in a three-page letter, partially
reproduced in Tuesday's editions of the tabloid, the best-selling
newspaper in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Blair sharply rejected claims Labor was ''beginning to lose the
next general election,'' and said that creating a strong economy is
''no small achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   He said 900,000 jobs had been created during his three years as
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Blair was reacting to a front-page story in The Sun bannered
''Mayday Mayday'' in which the newspaper said that ''it is only the
successful economy that is keeping Labor afloat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun singled out for criticism the uncertain future of Rover
cars, the furor over the rising number of asylum seekers, the
faltering Northern Ireland peace accord and the overburdened
National Health Service.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said Blair seemed particularly stung by the NHS
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the NHS I accept fully we cannot turn it round overnight,''
The Sun quoted him as writing. Blair noted that that there are
5,500 more nurses, saying that was a ''huge increase in the number
of nurses and midwives in training.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Northern Ireland, he wrote, ''A few years ago, over a
hundred lives a year were being lost. There was no peace process,
no cease-fire. There were daily bombings and killings. Now there is
a process. Whatever its difficulties, it is the only show in town.
In the last year, only seven were killed -- quite a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair added: ''So yes, there is a lot to do. But there has been
a lot done. And since the Tories are committed to scrapping most of
the changes we have made, there is a lot to lose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 2216 </TRAILER>
