<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   ----
Gertrude A. Barber:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ERIE, Pa. (AP) -- Gertrude A. Barber, who pioneered work with
people with developmental disabilities, died Saturday. She was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Barber was a civic leader who used her political clout to
improve the lives of mentally impaired people. The center named for
her operates group homes and other centers throughout Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gov. Tom Ridge presented Barber with a $2 million
check for Project 2000, a $7.5 million plan to build a national
institute for education, research and new services for people with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Barber was hired in 1933 by the Erie School District as a
special-education teacher. Later she was named assistant
superintendent of schools.
</P>
<P>
   Barber launched the Exceptional Children's Center in 1952, which
was the forerunner of the Barber centers.
Richard Bertram:
</P>
<P>
   STUART, Fla. (AP) -- Pioneer yacht manufacturer and offshore
powerboat champion Richard Bertram died Friday from complications
related to Parkinson's disease. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Bertram popularized the now-standard V-type hull that allows
boats to cut through rough waters.
</P>
<P>
   Bertram was competing in the 1958 America's Cup trials when he
noticed a small boat slicing through choppy waters. Intrigued by
the boat's V-shaped bottom, he tracked down the designer and asked
him to build a larger version so he could commute from his Coconut
Grove waterfront home to his office in downtown Miami.
</P>
<P>
   When the 30-foot ''Moppie'' was finished, Bertram entered the
boat in the 1960 Miami-Nassau race. The boat broke the course
record and beat the nearest competitors by two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''Moppie'' was featured in scores of newspaper articles, as well
as Sports Illustrated, and boaters asked for replicas. That's when
Bertram started his Miami business, building luxury cruising yachts
and sports-fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
   His clientele included Aristotle Onassis, the Aga Kahn, King
Hussein of Jordan and Prince Bertil of Sweden.
Mark Denis:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mark Denis, the voice of the Disneyland
Monorail and a fixture on Southern California radio for four
decades, died after suffering from a bacterial or viral infection
affecting the heart. He was 59.
</P>
<P>
   Denis, a radio traffic reporter for Los Angeles station KFI-AM,
began his career as a disc jockey in Hemet at tiny radio station
KHSJ-AM in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   He later moved to KFXM-AM in San Bernardino and KGB-AM in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Denis returned to Los Angeles in 1969, working at KFI and KEZY.
He immersed himself in traffic reporting in the 1980s and delivered
nearly 9,000 midday traffic reports each year on KFI and it's
sister station KOST-FM.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the disembodied, baritone voice of the Disneyland
Monorail, announcing sights on the tour of the amusement park and
directing guests to their destinations.
William Francis Gallagher:
</P>
<P>
   WEBSTER, Mass. (AP) -- William Francis Gallagher, a retired
president of the American Foundation for the Blind, died April 19
after a long illness. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher gave more than 40 years of service to enriching the
lives of people who were sight impaired. Blind since boyhood,
Gallagher joined the foundation in 1972 as director of program
planning and later served as director of advocacy. He became the
foundation's director in 1980 and its president in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, which also preserves the archives of Helen
Keller, credits Gallagher with helping improve standards for the
accreditation of specialized schools and agencies that offer
services to the blind.
Pham Van Dong:
</P>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Pham Van Dong, who served as Vietnam's
prime minister through three decades of war and reunification, died
Saturday. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Dong was among a few revolutionaries who wrested Vietnam from
the French, then defeated U.S.-backed South Vietnam to bring the
entire country under Hanoi's rule on April 30, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   While Ho Chi Minh was the visionary and father figure, and Gen.
Vo Nguyen Giap was the battlefield hero, Dong was the diplomat and
government organizer. He became prime minister of North Vietnam
soon after independence in 1954 and headed reunified Vietnam from
1976 to 1987.
</P>
<P>
   During the long war with the South, Dong was the North's main
spokesman to the world. Dong met with the handful of foreign
journalists and American anti-war activists who came to Hanoi, and
stressed his government's determination to keep fighting despite
punishing U.S. airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   But he was far from a heavy-handed propagandist. Adept at
charming visitors, he spiced his talk with quotes from French
classics and loud, disarming laughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-01-00 2216 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000501.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes from Monday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Yankees-Indians:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Entering Monday night's game, New York's relievers had
given up just six runs in their last nine games and hadn't allowed
a home run in the last 29 1-3 innings. At 7-0, the Yankees' bullpen
is also the only one without a loss this season. ... As competitive
as their matchups have been in the postseason, the New
York-Cleveland regular-season series have been fairly one-sided the
past few seasons. The Yankees were 7-3 vs. Cleveland last year and
have won the last four season series between the teams. ... New
York's 21-9 record is the best for any opponent at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Manager Charlie Manuel said No. 1 starter Bartolo
Colon, on the 15-day DL since April 16 with a pulled muscle in his
rib cage, will throw on the side Wednesday and will make a minor
league rehab start next week. ... The Indians' defense has been
steady and spectacular of late. Cleveland has not made an error in
its last four games and entered Monday leading the AL with a .987
fielding percentage. ... Manuel said he expects catcher Sandy
Alomar to come off the DL on time. Alomar has been out since April
with a pulled right hamstring.
Tigers-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: The Tigers were 1-82 last season in games they trailed
after eight innings. They were 0-15 in those situations this year
until beating the Chicago White Sox 4-3 in 12 innings Sunday. ...
Manager Phil Garner, third baseman Dean Palmer and pitcher Doug
Brocail served the fourth game of their suspensions for a brawl
April 22 with the Chicago White Sox. Garner and Palmer have four
more games to serve, while Brocail is eligible to play in Detroit's
next game. ... With Jeff Fassero pitching Monday and Pete Schourek
going Tuesday, the Tigers will have faced six lefty starters in 13
games. Righties started the first 12 games of the season against
them. ... C.J. Nitkowski had allowed just eight extra-base hits,
including four homers, to the 127 batters he faced this season. But
he gave up homers to Mike Stanley and Carl Everett in the first two
innings Monday.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Jose Offerman, Boston's leadoff hitter, finally got a
break when Red Sox manager Jimy Williams kept the slumping second
baseman out of the starting lineup for the first time this season.
A .280 career hitter, Offerman is batting .175 with 14 hits in 21
games. And he was hitless in his last 13 at bats. ''We need to give
him some time to work on some things,'' Williams said. ''This is
not a benching.'' ... Jeff Frye, who replaced Offerman, singled in
the first inning. ... With lefty Nitkowski pitching, Williams
benched two lefties -- Brian Daubach, hitting .354, and Trot Nixon,
hitting .310.
Athletics-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Oakland RHP Kevin Appier, once the ace of the Royals
staff, would have been a big draw pitching against his old team on
Tuesday. But he is on the DL with a strained forearm. Nevertheless,
the A's have been getting the best of the deal so far. Appier is
3-2 with Oakland this year while the three pitchers Kansas City got
in return -- Blake Stein, Brad Rigby and Jeff D'Amico -- have won two
games for the Royals. Stein is on the DL, Rigby has been dealt to
Montreal and D'Amico is at Triple-A Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals sent troubled starter Jay Witasick to
the bullpen Monday and moved Jeff Suppan to his start on Wednesday
against Oakland. Witasick was winless in four decisions with an ERA
of 8.46. ''I know he's been struggling,'' said manager Tony Muser.
''He's pressing. He's not feeling real good about himself and I
think he's thinking about his record.'''
Blue Jays-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays recalled OF Andy Thompson from Triple-A
Syracuse and placed OF Shannon Stewart on the DL retroactive to
April 29 with a right hamstring pull. Thompson was hitting .241
with one homer and seven RBIs. ... Frank Castillo will get the
start for the Blue Jays in Tuesday's game. The former Chicago Cubs
right-hander has struggled, going 0-2 with a 9.00 ERA in four
starts so far. ... The Blue Jays set a club mark with 43 homers in
April, eclipsing the former mark set in 1996 by one. ... Former
Chicago Bears quarterback Jim McMahon was a pre-game dugout guest
of Blue Jays pitcher David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: RF Magglio Ordonez decided not to appeal his five-game
suspension for his role in a brawl with Detroit last month. Ordonez
began serving it Monday. The White Sox moved Paul Konerko up from
fifth to cleanup to replace Ordonez in the batting order and used
Jeff Abbott to take his spot in right. RHP Tanyon Sturtze began
serving his three-game suspension. ... manager Jerry Manuel was
serving the fourth of his eight-game suspension and had hoped to
watch the game from a TV production truck located in a stadium
garage, but went home instead. ... Manuel said he would like to see
major league baseball send reps to spring training and lay out
guidelines on how brushback situations will be policed. ''They need
to go over that with each team,'' he said.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Astros-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: By going 9-14 in April, the Astros had their first
losing month since going 11-17 in May 1997. ... Roger Cedeno,
second in the NL last season with 66 steals, led the league with
nine going into Monday's game in Milwaukee. ... Richard Hidalgo has
been hit by a pitch seven times, which leads the league. He had
been hit only seven times in 749 previous at-bats. Hidalgo's
seventh HBP came in Sunday's 4-3 loss to the Astros, who lead the
NL by being hit 19 times in their first 23 games.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: The Brewers are impressed by the pitching of reliever
David Weathers, the winner in Sunday's game. Weathers (2-0) pitched
2 1-3 scoreless innings and lowered his ERA to 0.50. ''He's been
outstanding,'' manager Davey Lopes said. ''He's been the best he
can be.'' Pitching coach Bob Apodaca said, ''Right now he's as good
a relief pitcher as there is in the National League. He's doing
everything for us. He does it with outstanding, impeccable command
of his pitches.'' ... SS Mark Loretta surprised his manager by
laying down a perfect sacrifice bunt on an 0-2 count Sunday against
Shane Reynolds. It didn't figure in the scoring. ''It was a
beautiful bunt,'' Lopes said. ''I didn't know he was doing it. He
did it on his own.'' Said Loretta: I just felt I could get it down.
I was kind of surprised I missed the first two (attempts).''
Expos-Rockies:
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: OF Vladimir Guerrero saw his NL-leading average fall
from .452 to .410 after going 1-for-10 against San Francisco. The
dropoff came after he was hit in the right hand by Colorado RHP
Kevin Jarvis last Wednesday. Jarvis was Monday night's starter
against the Expos. ... LHP Graeme Lloyd, who signed as free agent
in December, is scheduled to have surgery on his left rotator cuff
Tuesday and will be out at least two months. He has not pitched for
the Expos this season. ... Manager Felipe Alou said RHP Jeremy
Powell will be called up from Triple-A Ottawa to start Tuesday's
game. ... Alou, who was a minor-league manager in Denver in 1981,
got philosophical when asked what it is like playing at altitude.
''A thousand days is a like a day to the Lord. Well, playing a day
in Coors Field is like playing 1,000 days for a player or
manager.''
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: RHP Rolando Arrojo, who is on the DL with a strained
hamstring, threw 60 pitches in a simulated game Monday and is
expected to return to the starting rotation Saturday in San
Francisco. ''I don't see any reason I shouldn't be ready,'' he
said. ... The Rockies will have to move someone out of the rotation
to make room for Arrojo. The odd-man out could be LHP Scott Karl.
... C Scott Servais is eligible to come off the DL Wednesday but
likely will not join the Rockies until Friday as he recovers from a
sprained ankle. ... RHP Jerry Dipoto will undergo season-ending
surgery Wednesday to repair a bulging disc below his neck.
Braves-Dodgers:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Reliever John Rocker, suspended for the season's first
two weeks for offensive remarks that appeared in Sports Illustrated
over the winter, trotted from the bullpen to the dugout about 45
minutes before the game began and was booed by the few thousand
fans in Dodger Stadium at the time. However, he was cheered by a
small group of Braves fans near the dugout. ''I think he screwed
up,'' said 28-year-old Jose Kerch, who came to the U.S. from
Venezuela six years ago and was wearing an Andres Galarraga jersey.
''He already apologized. We can all make a mistake. It's time to
forgive him.'' ... Galarraga, who didn't play last season because
of cancer, said despite being around a long time, he's never seen
anything like the 13-game winning streak the Braves brought into
the game. ''It's something different every night,'' he said. ...
The Braves entered the game with a big league-leading ERA of 3.08 --
obviously a key factor in their winning streak. ''We've had other
runs through the years,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ''It's always
been good pitching, timely hitting and a lot of breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: Gary Sheffield, who hasn't missed a start despite
spraining his right ankle in the season's first week, received a
scare before the game when he stepped on a baseball that was
underneath a tarpaulin near the batting cage and rolled his ankle.
After some 40 minutes of treatment, he took about 10 swings off a
batting tee and declared himself ready to play. ''It's sore,'' he
said. ''It was really sore last night, and it just so happened a
freak accident happened when it hurt the most.'' Sheffield, hitting
.349 with 10 homers and 22 RBIs, admitted to being scared at first,
but smiled and said, ''I'm going to keep going until it falls off,
I guess.'' ... The Dodgers were outscored 12-4 in losing a
three-game series at Atlanta last week. They outscored Florida
25-16 in sweeping a three-game weekend series at Dodger Stadium.
... Left-hander Carlos Perez, 2-1 with a 4.62 ERA and the scheduled
starter Wednesday, has given the Dodgers permission to option him
to the minors until May 31, if they so choose. A five-year player
can refuse a minor league assignment, and Perez reached that
anniversary Monday. ''He believes it's not an issue,'' GM Kevin
Malone said. ''He's pitched well.''
Mets-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Catcher Vance Wilson's stay with the Mets was a short
one. Wilson was recalled Saturday from Triple-A Norfolk after Mike
Piazza bruised his right wrist the night before in Colorado. On
Monday in San Francisco, Wilson was sent back Norfolk to make room
for pitcher Bill Pulsipher, who made his season debut in the opener
of a four-game series against the Giants. Wilson doubled his
previous stint with the Mets, when he was with the team for one day
last July 31. Meanwhile, Piazza missed a third straight game and
remains day-to-day while recovering from his wrist injury. ... New
York OF Derek Bell finished April with 40 hits, a club record. ...
Monday marked the nine-year anniversary of Rickey Henderson passing
Lou Brock as the top base stealer in major league history. The
Mets' left fielder was with the Oakland Athletics when he stole
third base at the Oakland Coliseum against the New York Yankees for
No. 939. Henderson now has 1,336 career stolen bases, two of which
have come this season before Monday night's game at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: Giants slugger Barry Bonds hit his 455th career
homer Sunday off Montreal's Carl Pavano to take sole possession of
21st place on the career list. Dave Winfield is next at 20th place
with 465 career homers. Bonds finished April with 10 home runs, the
second-highest in an opening month for his career. He homered 11
times in April 1996. The most homers he's hit in a month is 15,
which he did last August. ... Giants RF Ellis Burks missed a third
game Monday since straining his left quadriceps while legging out a
triple against Montreal on Friday. ''He's getting closer,'' manager
Dusty Baker said. ''Hopefully, in the next couple of days, he'll be
ready. But we've just got to be careful because we don't want to
set him back and lose him for a week to 10 days.''
Marlins-Padres
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Reliever Dan Miceli is the latest former Padres player
to make his first trip back to San Diego. Miceli was traded to the
Marlins for RHP Brian Meadows on Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: Going into Monday's game, the Padres had given up 25
runs on nine homers in five games. The damage included two grand
slams and four three-run homers. The Padres lost four of the five
games, including being swept by Atlanta during the weekend. ... The
Marlins are one of only three NL teams the Padres have a winning
all-time record against. Milwaukee and Colorado are the others.
</P>
</TEXT>
