<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prostate Patients Seek Communication  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN BACHMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Fewer than a third of prostate cancer patients
believe their doctors discussed all available treatments, and 49
percent of urologists consider patients ill-prepared to make such
decisions, according to a survey released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The large communication gap between urologists and patients
threatens effective treatment and points to the cancer's nature as
a taboo subject of frank discussion, said urology groups backing
the survey presented at the American Urological Association's
annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''There seems to be a disconnect between physicians and
patients,'' said Dr. David McLeod, director of urologic oncology at
Walter Reed Medical Center. McLeod, who wasn't involved in the
survey, is the surgeon who successfully treated former Sen. Bob
Dole and Army Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, funded by biotechnology company Amgen, polled 307
men diagnosed with the cancer and 302 urologists.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't explain it well,'' McLeod said of treatments.
</P>
<P>
   That's because doctors are frequently rushed by tight schedules
and because they often assume patients have performed more research
about the disease than they have.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the doctors -- 90 percent -- said they believed
patients used the Internet to learn about the disease. In fact,
only 19 percent said they researched online, opting instead for
newspaper and magazine articles, and talking with friends and
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Joe Torre, the New York Yankees manager, did
when he was diagnosed with prostate cancer in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God for my wife. I don't go in there on the Internet and
get information on stuff,'' Torre said Monday from Cleveland, where
his team had a game.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer of the prostate is the second most common type of cancer
found in American men. Early detection greatly increases the chance
of successful treatment. About 179,300 men were diagnosed with the
disease last year, while about 32,000 die from it annually.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: American Urological Association,
http://www.auanet.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
