<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Castro Leads May Day Parade
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Fidel Castro joined the annual May Day parade today for the
first time in years and ended a speech with a cell phone call to Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, urging him to continue his fight to bring his refugee son, Elian, home
to Cuba. Castro led hundreds of thousands of Cubans from Havana's Plaza of the
Revolution to the U.S. Interests Section. ''Fidel! Fidel!'' chanted the crowd in
the annual march that traditionally involves workers. In a speech, Castro
praised Cubans for their tenacity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Asked To Reject Elian Asylum
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Juan Miguel Gonzalez asked a federal appeals court today
to reject the political asylum claims filed on behalf of his son, Elian, by the
6-year-old Cuban refugee's Miami relatives. The father's motion was submitted to
the 11th U.S. Court of Appeals. The brief asked the appeals court to uphold a
March 21 ruling by a U.S. District judge in Miami that the court has no right to
second guess the government on matters of asylum. The appeals court has
scheduled a hearing for May 11.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Blair Rips May Day Demonstrators
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Anti-capitalist demonstrators clashed with police Monday in
central London, daubing anti-war slogans on the Cenotaph war memorial, tearing
down the golden arches of a McDonald's and spray-painting a hammer and sickle on
a statue of Winston Churchill in a May Day protest. Prime Minister Tony Blair
decried the demonstrators, saying, ''The people responsible for the damage
caused in London today are an absolute disgrace.'' He added, ''To deface the
Cenotaph and the statue of Winston Churchill is simply beneath contempt. It is
only because of the bravery and courage of our war dead that these idiots can
live in a free country at all.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Decried on Social Security
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- GOP presidential campaigner George W. Bush's plan for
Social Security was dismissed today by the White House as set ''in a world where
budgets don't exist.'' Bush is considering proposing -- as Republicans in
Congress have -- a plan through which workers could invest a portion of their
Social Security payroll taxes in the stock market. White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart said Bush needed to provide more details on his proposal and ''stop
talking about campaign promises in a vacuum.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Expects Palestinian State
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EILAT, Israel (AP) -- Trying to improve the climate in peace talks, Israeli
officials said Monday they've resigned themselves to Palestinian statehood, and
the Palestinians acknowledged Israel's pain on Holocaust Remembrance Day. But
negotiators reported little progress and awaited the arrival of a U.S. mediator
Tuesday to help draft an outline of a final peace treaty. Israeli officials said
they would not oppose a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, but
said the Palestinians should accept that some Jewish settlements there will
become part of Israel.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Anger Linked to Heart Attacks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- People who are highly anger-prone are nearly three times more
likely to have a heart attack, a study has found. The connection between anger
and heart attacks held true even after researchers took into account other major
risk factors such as high blood pressure, high cholesterol, smoking and obesity.
''The implications of our study are that anger could potentially lead to heart
attacks, especially among middle-aged men and women with normal blood
pressure,'' said Janice Williams, an epidemiologist in Atlanta who led the study
while at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average on Tuesday climbed 150.95 points to
18,554.03 in early trading, rising in line with gains in New York stocks and
higher futures prices in Chicago Mercantile Exchange. The Dow Jones industrial
average rose 77.87 points to close at 10,811.78 on Monday. The technology-heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 97.42 to close at 3,958.08.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Red Wings Ice Avalanche 3-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- The Detroit Red Wings turned to their Russian connection for
new life in their second-round playoff series with the Colorado Avalanche. The
Red Wings won goals from Igor Larionov and Sergei Fedorov tonight in a 3-1
victory over the Avs, who eliminated Detroit in the Western Conference
semifinals last season. The best-of-seven series continues with Game 4 on
Wednesday night at Joe Louis Arena. Game 5 will be Friday night in Denver.
</P>
