<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 23:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Opposes Trade Status for China  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government's new religious advisory panel
took strong stands Monday against two nations it accuses of abusing
Christians and others, calling for possible aid to Sudanese rebels
and rejection of permanent normal trade status for China.
</P>
<P>
	   The far-reaching advice of the U.S. Commission on International
Religious Freedom sparked criticism from an Islamic advocacy group
and dissent on the Sudanese recommendation by a Muslim leader on
the commission. The State Department immediately rejected the China
proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   The 10-member commission, formed last year to advise the
government on policies that will promote a global freedom to
worship, limited its report to Sudan, China and Russia. Panel
members include religious figures from several faiths, human rights
advocates and former diplomats.
</P>
<P>
	   China and Sudan ''are countries in which there are systematic,
egregious, ongoing manifestations of religious persecutions,''
Rabbi David Saperstein, the panel's chairman, told a news
conference releasing what is to be an annual report.
</P>
<P>
	   Russia has protected religious freedom dramatically better than
the former Soviet Union, the commission concluded, but Vice
Chairman Michael K. Young said the panel is concerned with
President Vladimir Putin's order to ''liquidate'' religions that
don't register by year's end in accordance with a 1997 law.
</P>
<P>
	   ''We urge that the U.S. make reversal of this decree an urgent
priority in its discussions with the Russian government,'' said
Young, dean of the George Washington University Law School.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission's sweeping recommendations included: tightened
sanctions against Sudan, nonlethal aid for opposition groups if no
improvements occur in a year, restrictions on U.S. stock offerings
that might help oppressive nations such as Sudan, denial of any bid
by China to host the Olympics and an invitation to the Dalai Lama
to address Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   ''While many commissioners support free trade, the commission
believes that the U.S. Congress should grant China Permanent Normal
Trade Relations (PNTR) status only after China makes substantial
improvement in respect for religious freedom,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton administration has made PNTR for China a major
priority. The status would give China's exports to the United
States the same favorable conditions that other nations enjoy and
ease China's entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
	   In a joint statement, Assistant Secretary of State Harold Hongju
Koh and special religious freedom Ambassador-at-large Robert Seiple
welcomed many of the commission's recommendations but rejected
tying religious rights to China trade.
</P>
<P>
	   ''We profoundly believe that conditionality will not advance the
cause of religious freedom in China, and will not improve the
circumstances of any of the religious adherents about whom we are
all deeply concerned,'' the officials said. At the same time, the
administration remains committed to promoting religious freedom in
China and elsewhere, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   Saperstein, director of the Religious Action Center of Reform
Judaism in Washington, said commission conclusions were unanimous
except for a dissent by member Laila Al-Marayati, a physician who
is past president of the Women's Muslim League.
</P>
<P>
	   Al-Marayati, who did not appear at the news conference, objected
to aid for the Sudanese People's Liberation Army, saying it could
undermine U.S. credibility in the region. She said the group has
committed human rights abuses and is internally divided.
</P>
<P>
	   Ibrahim Hooper of the Council on American-Islamic Relations said
Muslims have been concerned since the commission's inception that
it was ideologically and religiously motivated with a bias against
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
	   ''Our fears were not assuaged by the report,'' he said. ''We
don't mind people investigating religious and human rights abuses
worldwide if they use one central standard for all,'' Hooper said,
accusing the commission of glossing over abuses by Sudan's
Christian rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   On Russia and China, he said, the commission made only a passing
reference to the ''near genocide'' against Chechen Muslims and the
denial of religious freedom to millions of Muslims in China.
</P>
<P>
	   In support of proselytizing American churches, the commission
announced plans to develop U.S. policy options for promoting the
''right to change one's faith and the right to seek to persuade
others to change theirs.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.uscirf.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
