<HEADLINE> Salvador Election Outcome Protested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP)-- A conservative legislator was
elected president of the Salvadoran congress Monday, despite
protests from a party of former leftist rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Ciro Cruz, 54, of the National Conciliation Party, won on a 47-4
vote, with 32 abstentions. All but one of those abstaining was from
the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, FMLN. One legislator
was absent.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the former FMLN rebels for the first time won a
greater number of seats the ruling party, grabbing 31 of the 84
posts in the country's single-house congress. The ruling
Nationalist Republican Alliance holds 29 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative National Conciliation Party, which works
closely with the ruling party, holds 14 seats -- enough to keep
rightists in control of the Assembly. The remaining 10 seats are
held by other parties.
</P>
<P>
   The leftists organized themselves into a political party after
signing the 1992 peace accords, ending a 12-year civil war that
left 76,000 people dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
