<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-01 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Higher at Midday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar gained against the yen Tuesday morning
on signs the American economy is still going strong. Tokyo stocks
rose following Wall Street's rally.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 108.56 yen in late morning, up 0.58 yen from
late Monday but below its late New York level of 108.79 yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 77.81
points, or 0.42 percent, to 18,480.89 points at the end of the
morning session. On Monday, the average closed up 429.38 points, or
2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar's firmness remained intact on
the back of strength in U.S. financial markets and continued
strength in the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said, however, the greenback moved in a narrow range
during the morning trading in Tokyo ahead of Japan's ''Golden
Week'' holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets in Tokyo will be closed Wednesday through
Friday because of national holidays. The markets will reopen
Monday, May 8.
</P>
<P>
   In New York on Monday, the greenback's late level of 108.79 yen
was its highest level since March 1, when the currency bought
110.31 yen.
</P>
<P>
   Also supporting the dollar was new data showing the U.S. economy
continues to grow at a rapid pace.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Purchasing Management said Monday
that the U.S. manufacturing sector registered further growth in
April, and the government reported separately on a surprising rise
in construction spending in March.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 77.87
points to close at 10,811.78 on Monday. The technology-heavy Nasdaq
composite index rose 97.42 to close at 3,958.08.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 99.58 yen, up from
98.56 yen late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, prices started higher in line with gains in
New York stocks and higher futures prices in Monday's Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Trading remained in a lackluster prior to the start of a
five-day holiday period, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 13.37 points, or 0.79 percent, to 1,708.60
points. The TOPIX closed up 46.36 points, or 2.8 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.7400 percent from Monday's finish of 1.7350 percent. Its price
fell 0.04 point to 100.51.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Tokyo Stock Exchange: http://www.tse.or.jp./
</P>
</TEXT>
